1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:10,000
From the Library of Congress and the Smithsonian National Museum of African American History and Culture.

2
00:00:10,000 --> 00:00:23,000
Today is Thursday, July 20, 2011. My name is Joe Mosnier of the Southern oral history program at the University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill.

3
00:00:23,000 --> 00:00:42,000
I'm with videographer John Bishop on the Rutgers University campus in Newark NJ, New Jersey to do an oral history interview for the Civil Rights History Project that joined undertaking of the Library of Congress and the Smithsonian National Museum of African American History and Culture.

4
00:00:42,000 --> 00:00:53,000
I'm with the Library of Congress and Culture and we're delighted and privileged today to be with Mr. Junius Williams to talk about all of your work over the years and the movement and in the decades since.

5
00:00:53,000 --> 00:00:59,000
So Mr. Williams, thanks so much for the welcome to the campus and it's very nice to sit down with you. Thank you.

6
00:00:59,000 --> 00:01:05,000
Let me have you just to begin. Talk a little bit about where you were born, your parents, your family.

7
00:01:05,000 --> 00:01:26,000
I was born in Suffolk, Virginia and my parents were music teachers. My father was the first black band director in Richmond and my mother was the first coordinator of music in North Virginia for schools.

8
00:01:26,000 --> 00:01:30,000
So they had a big musical impact on my life.

9
00:01:30,000 --> 00:01:39,000
Do you have parents of Virginia? My parents are Virginians. My father is from Danville, my mother is from Suffolk.

10
00:01:39,000 --> 00:01:42,000
And how old were you when you moved from Suffolk over to Richmond?

11
00:01:42,000 --> 00:01:59,000
I was five, I'm told. So I don't have too much independent recollection of growing up in Suffolk. Although we went to Suffolk quite often in the summer when my parents were in summer school getting higher degrees or working toward that anyway.

12
00:01:59,000 --> 00:02:04,000
Where did they gotten their musical training?

13
00:02:04,000 --> 00:02:16,000
My mother went to Howard University and then transferred to the University of Pennsylvania. She got a degree in music education and my father got the same degree from West Virginia State.

14
00:02:16,000 --> 00:02:22,000
He was a violinist and a singer. She was a pianist and a singer.

15
00:02:22,000 --> 00:02:24,000
So it was a house full of music? House full of music.

16
00:02:24,000 --> 00:02:35,000
Yes, I have. Well, I had several siblings but my most immediate sibling was my brother John. We grew up at the same time. Then I had other half brothers and sisters.

17
00:02:35,000 --> 00:02:42,000
So you would have been, if you moved at five, you would have done your schooling in Richmond?

18
00:02:42,000 --> 00:02:50,000
I did. Can you talk a little bit about the community and neighborhood, the public school experience?

19
00:02:50,000 --> 00:03:02,000
We started school a little early because my brother, both my brother and I, turned five in the later part of the year.

20
00:03:02,000 --> 00:03:10,000
So my mother talked the officials into letting us start when we were four. So we were always a little younger than our peers.

21
00:03:10,000 --> 00:03:17,000
We already knew how to read. We already knew how to count. So that wasn't the issue. The issue was, should they have done it?

22
00:03:17,000 --> 00:03:27,000
And it didn't matter because she got us in there. Schools were segregated. She was a music teacher at the elementary schools and my father was a music teacher at the high school level.

23
00:03:27,000 --> 00:03:43,000
So school was, for us it was fun. We had a good time. There were challenging moments but nothing to do with race because we were insulated from that, from the impact of race.

24
00:03:43,000 --> 00:03:53,000
Partially because of our parents' middle class standing, partially because of the skillful way in which they negotiated the system to keep us safe.

25
00:03:53,000 --> 00:04:05,000
So we grew up on north side of town, which was a working class, middle class area, moved from North Avenue to Barton Avenue with my parents bought a house.

26
00:04:05,000 --> 00:04:24,000
And I remember high school in particular, there was a moment in which I had to decide whether I was going to go to high school across the high school in the north western side.

27
00:04:24,000 --> 00:04:32,000
I guess it was more west, Richmond, I'm trying to think exactly the sector that Walker was in. But that's where most of my friends were going to Maggie Walker.

28
00:04:32,000 --> 00:04:45,000
But my father told it Armstrong. My father wanted me to come to Armstrong. He said that was a better school. I didn't want to go because my friends were going to Walker. But he persuaded me to come to Armstrong.

29
00:04:45,000 --> 00:04:54,000
In Richmond at that time there were two high schools for black people. You either went to Walker or you went to Armstrong.

30
00:04:54,000 --> 00:05:08,000
And just to let you know how that rival played out, everything's given we had a football classic. It wasn't just a game, it was a classic. The Maggie Walker Armstrong classic.

31
00:05:08,000 --> 00:05:25,000
And it was so big they had to put it in city stadium. There were 30,000 people who came to that game every year. You either were for Armstrong or you for Walker. If you didn't graduate, it didn't matter. If you associated with one or the other, you were for that team.

32
00:05:25,000 --> 00:05:33,000
So that was one of the benefits of segregation. It kind of ordered our lives socially for us. We knew who we were and where we stood.

33
00:05:33,000 --> 00:05:54,000
Did you have more you an athlete? Is that something that you're a football player? No, I played, well, I played tennis. The football players didn't consider that a sport. But not until Arthur Ashe became a champion. So I grew up with Arthur. As a matter of fact, Arthur was one of the people who went to Walker and eventually went to high school. I believe somewhere in Los Angeles maybe. I'm not so sure.

34
00:05:54,000 --> 00:06:14,000
But he went out of town to play tennis. So when Arthur began to get national prominence as the first black in tennis, a lot of the athletes had to change their mind about that. And I was glad because by that time I had learned to play tennis. I played with Arthur a little bit, which is to say, Arthur beat me in tennis.

35
00:06:14,000 --> 00:06:24,000
I think in doubles, we once got three games out of two sets against Arthur and his partner.

36
00:06:24,000 --> 00:06:43,000
Did your family was it was church a part of your life coming up? Oh, yeah. Oh, yeah. Baptist. My father taught music. I was a music director at one church and my mother had several cries at Ebenezer Baptist Church.

37
00:06:43,000 --> 00:06:53,000
That's when my brother and I went. Music was a part of our life wherever we turned.

38
00:06:53,000 --> 00:07:08,000
So born in 43. So by a mid-decade in the 50s, you're 12, 13 years old. Were the events of, I'm not thinking about things like the Brown decision about Emmett Till, about Montgomery.

39
00:07:08,000 --> 00:07:32,000
Little Rock. Was your household a tenor in an outfit conversation away to those things? Yes, because of Jet magazine and Ebony magazine. The picture of Emmett Till sticks in my mind now. That open casket picture in Chicago when over the 50,000 people filed by it to see his bloated, disfigured body.

40
00:07:32,000 --> 00:07:51,000
I was a year younger or maybe two years younger than Emmett Till and I had to just picture myself in that same situation. So we got mad, mad, mad. That was one of the sparks that really lit the civil rights movement in a lot of people's hearts, whether we did anything or not.

41
00:07:51,000 --> 00:07:59,000
And then there were some victories that we had also along the civil rights front of our own making.

42
00:07:59,000 --> 00:08:12,000
At a certain point, there was a festival called the Tobacco Festival Parade because Richmond was a big tobacco town. They processed tobacco there.

43
00:08:12,000 --> 00:08:20,000
So it was usually segregated. The white bands were supposed to be in the front, black bands in the back.

44
00:08:20,000 --> 00:08:32,000
My father said, we're not going to march in the back. And the other music teacher at Walker said the same thing. Joe Kennedy, very prominent musician in his own right.

45
00:08:32,000 --> 00:08:52,000
And so we did, but at some point they said, okay, we're going to integrate it. So there was this moment when we had four high schools, two white, two black, that were meeting at the gathering point in the West End of town, getting ready to march in the parade.

46
00:08:52,000 --> 00:09:06,000
There was Armstrong and Walker on two corners and then across the street on the other were John Marshall and Thomas Jefferson. Those were the two main white schools.

47
00:09:06,000 --> 00:09:21,000
So of course the whites presumed to practice first and they did it with the drummers. The drummers were very mental, very sophisticated and polished rudimental drummers.

48
00:09:21,000 --> 00:09:41,000
And we laughed because we knew Armstrong's drummers were precise, but we had soul and we kicked there, but there lay dead one of the great rules of white supremacy that they could do it better than we could.

49
00:09:41,000 --> 00:10:02,000
And we saw it for ourselves. So we had a victory. That was our first civil rights victory in my family because we talked about that forever. And of course we marched gloriously. I mean we marched like we had never marched before. And there were black and white people cheering us along Broad Street in New York. I get tearier, I just think about that.

50
00:10:02,000 --> 00:10:09,000
I'm sorry, that was enrichment. So these would have been that would have been during your high school year. Yeah, you want me to say that again? No, no, no.

51
00:10:09,000 --> 00:10:26,000
Did you have mentioned to me earlier when we were chatting before we started the interview that you thought very seriously about taking music, making music you life and going to school to study music and college? How did you resolve upon the path for the animals?

52
00:10:26,000 --> 00:10:46,000
Well, my father was a professional musician. He had played in some bands in Atlantic City where he grew up in other places. And he knew what the life of an artinetic musician was playing in bands. So he did not let me play in the pickup bands in Richmond. I was good on alto saxophone and people asked me to play.

53
00:10:46,000 --> 00:10:57,000
But he said, nope, can't do it. I'm not going to let you play. I didn't do that. And then they discouraged me from becoming a musician because they didn't want me to have that kind of life of performance on the road.

54
00:10:57,000 --> 00:11:15,000
Nor did they want me to be a music teacher in school because they said that was too precarious in terms of the money. But I wanted to be a musician. So I applied to North Western because I saw that band on television at some football game, some big 10 football game. And I said, that's where I want to go to school.

55
00:11:15,000 --> 00:11:43,000
Because of the band. And I saw myself in that band. I played clarinet saxophone and drums at that point. And I was pretty good on all of them. So I knew I would have a chance at least to get into that band. So I got accepted in North Western because I had good grades. I was valedictorian in my class. I had a 3.96 out of a 4.0 average. But they didn't give me any money.

56
00:11:43,000 --> 00:11:55,000
Amherst College on the other hand, which was recommended by a friend in the family who had gone to Amherst and was just graduating the year before.

57
00:11:55,000 --> 00:12:08,000
Said that's the best small college in the country. I didn't know Amherst from Edison. But they gave me a free ride. They gave me the full package, full scholarship.

58
00:12:08,000 --> 00:12:26,000
So of course, there was no doubt I was going to Amherst. And ironically, the music program was so bad that I put my saxophone down and didn't pick it up for most of the four years that I was there. Until one day, this guy came up from the movement one day.

59
00:12:26,000 --> 00:12:36,000
Because my place was always available for people who needed rest and relaxation. Because the guy came up from Mississippi. I won't mention his name because of what I'm going to say about him.

60
00:12:36,000 --> 00:12:51,000
But he had a harmonic on. He was blowing it. He thought he was a blues man, but he couldn't play that hard. So the next day, it was a Monday. I went over to the music store, which was next door to my, my, my, where I was staying in the fraternity house.

61
00:12:51,000 --> 00:13:01,000
And I got a C harmonic. I brought it back. I just took to it. It took to me. And I've been playing it every set.

62
00:13:01,000 --> 00:13:18,000
If you cross play, you know, the cross feel. G. I could play it mostly in G because that's where you get the full blues effect. And if you play it in C, you only on a limited basis.

63
00:13:18,000 --> 00:13:37,000
And so most of us play a fourth above the piano. Most blues hop are tuned are playing one fourth above the piano play or the guitar play. Whoever's got the concert seats.

64
00:13:37,000 --> 00:13:55,000
Before you even though before you even before you departed for Amherst and fall 61, the active demonstration phase, the movement had come to come into your world. And I am interested in your recollections about events around Virginia Union in 1960.

65
00:13:55,000 --> 00:14:10,000
Yeah, Virginia Union 1960 or early 1961, Charles Sherrod, who was the head of the Black students up at Virginia Union University, led a series of demonstrations and

66
00:14:10,000 --> 00:14:30,000
citizens at the department stores downtown Richmond, Millenrose, tall hammers, Cresquis. I'm not so sure where it was because I never got that close. I told my parents I wanted to join and they said, oh, no, the college students said they don't want any high school students involved.

67
00:14:30,000 --> 00:14:41,000
When I met Charles Sherrod, I asked him, was that true? Did you guys really say you didn't want high schools students because we couldn't be nonviolent? He said no.

68
00:14:41,000 --> 00:14:49,000
So that was just my mother and father's clever way of keeping me out of homes way as they saw it, little did they know.

69
00:14:50,000 --> 00:15:04,000
So they whisked me off to Amherst College in 1961, but the fire was still burning because I knew I had to do something because I couldn't just let everybody else do it and I wasn't going to do it.

70
00:15:04,000 --> 00:15:18,000
So eventually we formed, I was a part of the civil rights group there and we were in support of civil rights, but at some point on another it was time for me to go south. So that's what happened in 1965.

71
00:15:18,000 --> 00:15:24,000
Yeah, let me ask about this is also interesting. I want to move with some care and a little bit more slowly.

72
00:15:24,000 --> 00:15:25,000
Sorry.

73
00:15:25,000 --> 00:15:40,000
I'm interested in, you've just mentioned this incident with your folks who were there looking out for their child and wanting to make sure that you're clear of the tensions and perspective dangers of early citizens in Richmond.

74
00:15:40,000 --> 00:15:54,000
What was the relationship that prevailed between your parents on those kinds of questions and how were your views and perspectives developing in New Year's just towards the end of high school around the civil rights question?

75
00:15:54,000 --> 00:16:06,000
Well, first it was Emmett Till. Then it was news about the Montgomery bus boycott and the rise of this man called Martin Luther King.

76
00:16:06,000 --> 00:16:16,000
And so we talked about all those things. It was clear things were changing and of course we all knew about the brown case.

77
00:16:16,000 --> 00:16:30,000
But other than those small victories that we had such as the Armstrong Walker versus Thomas Jefferson, John Marshall, little dual, we didn't see much change.

78
00:16:30,000 --> 00:16:43,000
So it was talked about it until the students demonstrated. And of course my parents were in favor of that. But they thought that was dangerous. There was another moment.

79
00:16:43,000 --> 00:16:54,000
At some point after the Montgomery bus boycott, the lawsuit came about that integrated said you got to integrate bus transportation throughout the south.

80
00:16:54,000 --> 00:17:12,000
So Richmond complied. So one day the word went out. The buses are now desegregated.

81
00:17:12,000 --> 00:17:20,000
So my parents got hold of the news and told Johnny and me because they knew we were going to try it.

82
00:17:20,000 --> 00:17:26,000
They said now when you get on that bus, I want you to be careful. Don't do this. Don't do that.

83
00:17:26,000 --> 00:17:43,000
And I'm sure that was the conversation held in many homes around Richmond that day with black parents trying to protect us.

84
00:17:43,000 --> 00:17:52,000
So we got on the bus and sure enough we sat down in the closest seat we could to the driver.

85
00:17:52,000 --> 00:18:07,000
We sat down so close that we could see the color of his neck, which was red when we sat in those seats because nobody else had done it.

86
00:18:07,000 --> 00:18:14,000
Don't you just pick it up. You're just answering.

87
00:18:14,000 --> 00:18:17,000
Okay, good. Where are you going to start?

88
00:18:17,000 --> 00:18:22,000
We're still on the phone and we're obviously so pleased that you were talking about these.

89
00:18:22,000 --> 00:18:30,000
We got on the bus and we got on the bus. And there was nobody seated in the front seats at all.

90
00:18:30,000 --> 00:18:36,000
And most of the older black people were still sitting in the back of the bus.

91
00:18:36,000 --> 00:18:44,000
So we sat down and we were closer enough to the driver so that I could see the color of his neck, which was red at that point.

92
00:18:44,000 --> 00:18:48,000
He wasn't too happy about this.

93
00:18:48,000 --> 00:18:53,000
And we started laughing and smiling amongst ourselves because we had done it.

94
00:18:53,000 --> 00:19:03,000
And it was the first time that the older black people who got who were on the bus, they smiled.

95
00:19:03,000 --> 00:19:05,000
They smiled at us.

96
00:19:05,000 --> 00:19:14,000
Because we had done something, I get a little emotional about that.

97
00:19:14,000 --> 00:19:18,000
We had done something they wanted to do for a long time.

98
00:19:19,000 --> 00:19:30,000
And so after the novelty war, which was within a couple of days, we all choked back to the back of the bus where we could cut up like kids like to do.

99
00:19:30,000 --> 00:19:35,000
But it was a new relationship between us and the older people by that point.

100
00:19:35,000 --> 00:19:40,000
But probably after time went on, they still looked at us and told us to be quiet when we were getting to noise it.

101
00:19:40,000 --> 00:19:46,000
But just for that magic moment in time, we did something they couldn't do for themselves.

102
00:19:46,000 --> 00:19:52,000
And then the gradually integration just kind of stole its way onto the public transportation system in Richmond.

103
00:19:52,000 --> 00:19:55,000
A couple more questions about coming up in Richmond.

104
00:19:55,000 --> 00:20:07,000
Did you ever, among newer family members, or folks who knew well, as for some unfortunate common experiences of violence around grace?

105
00:20:07,000 --> 00:20:19,000
We lived in a, when we bought the house, when my parents bought the house on Barton Avenue, there was a steep wooded ravine and on the other side white people still lived.

106
00:20:19,000 --> 00:20:24,000
So white boys used to shoot at us with BB guns.

107
00:20:24,000 --> 00:20:27,000
We in turn made weapons.

108
00:20:27,000 --> 00:20:32,000
We had bamboo growing in the odds that we made, and it was slaked coming from the roof.

109
00:20:32,000 --> 00:20:36,000
So we made a Tommy Hawks and spears and arrows and all that.

110
00:20:36,000 --> 00:20:39,000
But we couldn't get within range to use them.

111
00:20:39,000 --> 00:20:41,000
There was another street, and that was kind of comical.

112
00:20:41,000 --> 00:20:44,000
One point there was a little breach.

113
00:20:44,000 --> 00:20:53,000
The guys came over and I ended up getting shot in the hand with a BB gun trying to make friends with some of them.

114
00:20:53,000 --> 00:20:58,000
Because I was holding up something for one of them to shoot at, and he ended up shooting me.

115
00:20:58,000 --> 00:21:01,000
So I think that was a lesson learned.

116
00:21:01,000 --> 00:21:07,000
So that was how I guess our moment of daytime, if you will.

117
00:21:07,000 --> 00:21:09,000
Is that shooting was unintentional that he didn't?

118
00:21:09,000 --> 00:21:11,000
I don't think he was, I don't think he wanted to do it.

119
00:21:11,000 --> 00:21:13,000
I don't think he wanted to shoot it.

120
00:21:13,000 --> 00:21:16,000
At other points he probably would have, but not at that point.

121
00:21:16,000 --> 00:21:18,000
So he went back where he lived.

122
00:21:18,000 --> 00:21:21,000
I went in the house and got something to put on my hand.

123
00:21:21,000 --> 00:21:30,000
There was a street, though, called Brooklyn Park Boulevard, in the north side of Richmond, where whites lived totally on the other side.

124
00:21:30,000 --> 00:21:32,000
And we didn't dare go across that street.

125
00:21:32,000 --> 00:21:34,000
So I never went over there to test them.

126
00:21:34,000 --> 00:21:40,000
We went on the avenue sometimes to buy ice cream at highs, but that was it, HIGS highs.

127
00:21:40,000 --> 00:21:42,000
So that was about it.

128
00:21:42,000 --> 00:21:46,000
We went to buy ice cream at highs, and my mother loved to do that.

129
00:21:46,000 --> 00:21:56,000
But to other than go up there to participate as consumers in these merchant stores, that's about the only interaction we had.

130
00:21:56,000 --> 00:22:00,000
I had no white friends in my own age.

131
00:22:00,000 --> 00:22:02,000
I repeat that.

132
00:22:02,000 --> 00:22:07,000
I had no white friends in Richmond of my own age.

133
00:22:07,000 --> 00:22:13,000
We were just about totally insulated at school.

134
00:22:13,000 --> 00:22:22,000
There was one Russian professor at school at Armstrong, but all of my other teachers were black.

135
00:22:22,000 --> 00:22:30,000
In church, black, there were some black professionals we saw in the medical profession.

136
00:22:30,000 --> 00:22:36,000
I had asthma, so I had to go to an asthma specialist, and he was black.

137
00:22:36,000 --> 00:22:42,000
Except for the doctors, we saw, that was pretty much it.

138
00:22:42,000 --> 00:22:46,000
Yeah, that one white member of faculty at the high school, Russian.

139
00:22:46,000 --> 00:22:48,000
Did he happen to be Jewish?

140
00:22:48,000 --> 00:22:50,000
I didn't take question.

141
00:22:50,000 --> 00:23:00,000
Just before heading off to Amherst again, I didn't fall at 61.

142
00:23:00,000 --> 00:23:10,000
That period was pretty busy with Greenboro and Virginia Union and Hill and Freedom Rides.

143
00:23:10,000 --> 00:23:16,000
When did the idea of becoming a lawyer enter into your thinking and did it relate at all to the civil rights question?

144
00:23:16,000 --> 00:23:22,000
It kind of stole into my consciousness that that might be something I could do.

145
00:23:22,000 --> 00:23:35,000
I was at Amherst College, but my major thought was that I was going to go south and be in the movement and become a professional movement person, whatever that was.

146
00:23:35,000 --> 00:23:43,000
I wanted to be with SNCC, I wanted to be a SNCC field secretary, I wanted to organize people to do whatever had to be done at that particular time.

147
00:23:43,000 --> 00:23:46,000
My parents put that idea in my head.

148
00:23:46,000 --> 00:23:50,000
I remember they didn't want me to be a musician, but lawyers were fine.

149
00:23:50,000 --> 00:23:53,000
If I had wanted to be a doctor, they would have encouraged that too.

150
00:23:53,000 --> 00:23:56,000
But clearly, I was not on the science math trip.

151
00:23:56,000 --> 00:23:59,000
They said, well, why don't you become a lawyer?

152
00:23:59,000 --> 00:24:04,000
They kept pushing that program because they saw where I was going with the civil rights thing.

153
00:24:04,000 --> 00:24:08,000
I was telling them about things I was doing on campus.

154
00:24:08,000 --> 00:24:13,000
When I came home doing spring break, I was doing voter registration enrichment.

155
00:24:13,000 --> 00:24:20,000
I did voter registration in Springfield, Massachusetts, which was right around the corner from Amherst.

156
00:24:20,000 --> 00:24:25,000
I had this conference called the Civil Rights Movement Reform or Revolution.

157
00:24:25,000 --> 00:24:32,000
I had a group of others carried that conference out.

158
00:24:32,000 --> 00:24:36,000
It was the winter of 1965.

159
00:24:36,000 --> 00:24:40,000
About 1,000 people came from all of these coasts to that conference.

160
00:24:40,000 --> 00:24:42,000
They saw where I was going.

161
00:24:42,000 --> 00:24:44,000
Why don't you be a lawyer?

162
00:24:44,000 --> 00:24:47,000
I thought about it and I said, well, maybe so, but not now.

163
00:24:47,000 --> 00:24:54,000
I could see being a lawyer, being a civil rights lawyer because I knew of the great civil rights lawyers in the Brown tradition.

164
00:24:54,000 --> 00:24:58,000
As a matter of fact, Oliver Hill was a neighbor.

165
00:24:58,000 --> 00:25:03,000
He was a good friend, became a better friend after my mother passed.

166
00:25:03,000 --> 00:25:07,000
But she went to Howard at the same time.

167
00:25:07,000 --> 00:25:12,000
He was a law student and she was an undergraduate at Howard at the same time.

168
00:25:12,000 --> 00:25:16,000
So living in Richmond, we went to the same church.

169
00:25:16,000 --> 00:25:23,000
So it was kind of like, there's a little story there because one time we were talking,

170
00:25:23,000 --> 00:25:32,000
he said he was driving through Suffolk on the way to Norfolk to argue the case for equal pay for the teachers.

171
00:25:32,000 --> 00:25:36,000
And he got stopped by the police.

172
00:25:36,000 --> 00:25:42,000
And so he said, the first person he called was my grandfather, Junius White.

173
00:25:42,000 --> 00:25:47,000
Because he had to get somebody to vouch for him to get out of jail.

174
00:25:47,000 --> 00:25:53,000
And my grandfather was well respected as a businessman, churchman in the town.

175
00:25:53,000 --> 00:26:01,000
So the white people in charge said if Junius White says he's okay, then we're going to let him out on bail.

176
00:26:01,000 --> 00:26:03,000
They didn't know what he was doing, of course.

177
00:26:03,000 --> 00:26:06,000
They had no idea he was going down to try that case.

178
00:26:06,000 --> 00:26:10,000
Otherwise, Junius White or anybody couldn't stop him from keeping him.

179
00:26:10,000 --> 00:26:15,000
So that's the way that went.

180
00:26:15,000 --> 00:26:19,000
I wanted to be a lawyer because they wanted me to be a lawyer more than anything else.

181
00:26:19,000 --> 00:26:23,000
So this is what I said.

182
00:26:23,000 --> 00:26:28,000
I will apply to two law schools.

183
00:26:28,000 --> 00:26:32,000
If I get in one of those two, I'll go.

184
00:26:32,000 --> 00:26:35,000
If not, I'm going south.

185
00:26:35,000 --> 00:26:43,000
So they said, okay, but they didn't understand the high stakes poker I was playing because I only applied to Columbia and Yale.

186
00:26:43,000 --> 00:26:47,000
And I said, well, what the hell if I get in there, I'll go.

187
00:26:47,000 --> 00:26:53,000
I was not going to spend all my time filling out forms for seven law schools.

188
00:26:53,000 --> 00:26:56,000
And I didn't want to go to any of them anyway.

189
00:26:56,000 --> 00:26:58,000
And I got in.

190
00:26:58,000 --> 00:27:04,000
But by this time Tom Hayden had approached me, but we might be getting a little ahead of the story.

191
00:27:04,000 --> 00:27:06,000
Yeah, we'll come back to that.

192
00:27:06,000 --> 00:27:08,000
Let me ask you to tell it's really interesting.

193
00:27:08,000 --> 00:27:13,000
I have to say, Oliver Hill, that's not a pretty substantial role model.

194
00:27:13,000 --> 00:27:17,000
He was quite a firm.

195
00:27:17,000 --> 00:27:20,000
And the firm of Hill, Tucker and Mars, they were there too.

196
00:27:20,000 --> 00:27:23,000
They were all my family friends.

197
00:27:23,000 --> 00:27:31,000
What did you say, thinking about thinking about folks like Mr. Hill and his law partners and your folks in the community?

198
00:27:31,000 --> 00:27:45,000
As you think back, who would you say probably, you know, that question about who shaped you most, who most influenced the way you came up and began to think about yourself as a young adult man?

199
00:27:45,000 --> 00:27:48,000
My father.

200
00:27:48,000 --> 00:27:54,000
Yeah, he was my kind of, I guess he was, he was my role model.

201
00:27:54,000 --> 00:27:58,000
I like the way he talked to people.

202
00:27:58,000 --> 00:28:01,000
I like the popularity that he had.

203
00:28:01,000 --> 00:28:05,000
The kids call him pop Williams.

204
00:28:05,000 --> 00:28:09,000
He would sit on the front porch and speak to everybody who passed.

205
00:28:09,000 --> 00:28:13,000
My mother said, when he's speaking to them for, you don't know them.

206
00:28:13,000 --> 00:28:15,000
I just like to speak to people.

207
00:28:15,000 --> 00:28:18,000
I speak to people not if I see them in the street.

208
00:28:18,000 --> 00:28:20,000
I speak to people.

209
00:28:20,000 --> 00:28:24,000
So I would say he was probably my biggest closest role model.

210
00:28:24,000 --> 00:28:32,000
What was the experience like coming out of segregated Richmond and landing as a college freshman in Amherst, Massachusetts?

211
00:28:32,000 --> 00:28:37,000
Well, these are the best of times and these are the worst of times.

212
00:28:37,000 --> 00:28:44,000
My mother's plan was get them out of the clutches of segregation.

213
00:28:44,000 --> 00:28:45,000
You need to do that.

214
00:28:45,000 --> 00:28:48,000
You need to go to the best schools.

215
00:28:48,000 --> 00:28:53,000
Now, she had gone to Howard and she had gone to University of Pennsylvania.

216
00:28:53,000 --> 00:28:56,000
So she had some credentials to speak about both.

217
00:28:56,000 --> 00:29:01,000
My father had gone to West Virginia State, which was a land-grant black college out there.

218
00:29:01,000 --> 00:29:03,000
He didn't have too much to say about this.

219
00:29:03,000 --> 00:29:06,000
He, as far as he was concerned, black colleges were fine.

220
00:29:06,000 --> 00:29:08,000
But she didn't want us to go to black colleges.

221
00:29:08,000 --> 00:29:10,000
That was straight out her opinion.

222
00:29:10,000 --> 00:29:13,000
She went to a white school and in the north.

223
00:29:13,000 --> 00:29:16,000
And so she engineered that and got us ready.

224
00:29:16,000 --> 00:29:21,000
We went to summer courses at various places, whatever,

225
00:29:21,000 --> 00:29:24,000
whatever special preparatory things she could find.

226
00:29:24,000 --> 00:29:26,000
My brother and I went to those.

227
00:29:26,000 --> 00:29:30,000
And we went to camp in New Jersey and somewhere else.

228
00:29:30,000 --> 00:29:36,000
So we were socially accustomed to white people, not through Richmond,

229
00:29:36,000 --> 00:29:39,000
but because of our summers away from Richmond.

230
00:29:39,000 --> 00:29:42,000
So there was no culture shock in that respect.

231
00:29:42,000 --> 00:29:47,000
What was a culture shock was the fact that we were there

232
00:29:47,000 --> 00:29:52,000
and couldn't retreat and go anywhere else back to our own little enclave

233
00:29:52,000 --> 00:29:56,000
as we could after the summer was over with those other programs.

234
00:29:56,000 --> 00:29:58,000
So there I was.

235
00:29:58,000 --> 00:30:02,000
I wore a yellow sweater and had a big smile on.

236
00:30:02,000 --> 00:30:05,000
And that's what I remember my image was.

237
00:30:05,000 --> 00:30:07,000
Most of the time.

238
00:30:07,000 --> 00:30:15,000
People would come up and say, you're not like most of the colored people that we know.

239
00:30:15,000 --> 00:30:17,000
Or most of the Negroes that we know.

240
00:30:17,000 --> 00:30:20,000
And then they'd go in and tell some anecdotal something or other

241
00:30:20,000 --> 00:30:25,000
that was totally irrelevant and hurting.

242
00:30:25,000 --> 00:30:28,000
And I would just smile and keep going.

243
00:30:28,000 --> 00:30:35,000
And social life was absolutely horrible

244
00:30:35,000 --> 00:30:41,000
because the way it was structured at Amherst and all of those other colleges,

245
00:30:41,000 --> 00:30:45,000
you gotta understand, Amherst was all men at that point.

246
00:30:45,000 --> 00:30:54,000
So there were four black people in each class and then that'd been that way forever more.

247
00:30:54,000 --> 00:30:58,000
So there's a little mixed reaction that I have.

248
00:30:58,000 --> 00:31:03,000
I really appreciated Dean Wilson who came and recruited me to come to Amherst.

249
00:31:03,000 --> 00:31:08,000
And maybe but for him they would have been less.

250
00:31:08,000 --> 00:31:10,000
But there was a quota.

251
00:31:10,000 --> 00:31:16,000
So those who speak about against quotas, remember they have been quotas for a long time and still are.

252
00:31:16,000 --> 00:31:18,000
But that's another story.

253
00:31:18,000 --> 00:31:20,000
So there were four plus four plus four.

254
00:31:20,000 --> 00:31:24,000
And at Smith College, there were four at Mount Holyoke College.

255
00:31:24,000 --> 00:31:29,000
There were four and that there was no other, there were Hampshire College wasn't there at the time.

256
00:31:29,000 --> 00:31:34,000
And of course at UMass, which was a big state school, a mile away, actually closest,

257
00:31:34,000 --> 00:31:40,000
there was a whole class barrier there but they didn't have very much,

258
00:31:40,000 --> 00:31:43,000
it wasn't very much different down there either.

259
00:31:43,000 --> 00:31:51,000
Now I say that because most of the dating by Amherst guys was done in Smith and Holyoke.

260
00:31:51,000 --> 00:31:54,000
I didn't care about going to UMass.

261
00:31:54,000 --> 00:31:56,000
It was just very few people down there.

262
00:31:56,000 --> 00:32:01,000
I don't know if any people in my class who were black and the young ladies at that time who was there.

263
00:32:01,000 --> 00:32:08,000
And I certainly wasn't going to be the one who was going to try to do the interracial dating thing at that point in my life.

264
00:32:08,000 --> 00:32:10,000
It just wasn't done.

265
00:32:10,000 --> 00:32:13,000
I look at the interracial couples that I see now.

266
00:32:13,000 --> 00:32:16,000
It's very casual in America, America's change in every spec.

267
00:32:16,000 --> 00:32:19,000
But at that time it just wasn't done.

268
00:32:19,000 --> 00:32:29,000
So whenever I was put in a situation where I had to seek out and be friends with a person of the other sex,

269
00:32:29,000 --> 00:32:33,000
it was always iffy.

270
00:32:33,000 --> 00:32:37,000
You asked somebody to dance at one of those God awful mixes.

271
00:32:37,000 --> 00:32:41,000
I got told no more times than I got told yes.

272
00:32:41,000 --> 00:32:48,000
So if I, and on those yes occasions, it was always, it's seemingly, we're not always.

273
00:32:48,000 --> 00:32:55,000
But most of the times it was just, well, I don't want to embarrass you and I don't want to appear to be other than what I am.

274
00:32:55,000 --> 00:32:58,000
So I'll go ahead and do you a favor.

275
00:32:58,000 --> 00:33:00,000
That's basically the way it was.

276
00:33:00,000 --> 00:33:01,000
But the guys were good.

277
00:33:01,000 --> 00:33:05,000
I mean, I had good remates.

278
00:33:05,000 --> 00:33:09,000
Other than those people who questioned me about various things.

279
00:33:09,000 --> 00:33:20,000
The people that I was associated with at Pratt Dormitory in my first year were basically good guys.

280
00:33:20,000 --> 00:33:23,000
Now I ran, I ran.

281
00:33:23,000 --> 00:33:30,000
I participated in the rush in my freshman year for fraternities.

282
00:33:30,000 --> 00:33:38,000
Because the Emirates at that time was about 95% fraternity because that's the only place you could go to have girls in the rooms or in the,

283
00:33:38,000 --> 00:33:40,000
throughout the house, so to speak.

284
00:33:40,000 --> 00:33:45,000
The social life in the dorms was really, really, really slim.

285
00:33:45,000 --> 00:33:48,000
So that's the way they encouraged fraternities.

286
00:33:48,000 --> 00:33:50,000
They have no fraternities now.

287
00:33:50,000 --> 00:33:54,000
But at that time, that was part of the social fabric.

288
00:33:54,000 --> 00:33:58,000
That was part of the culture, rushing in your freshman year.

289
00:33:58,000 --> 00:34:04,000
So I was approached by several houses.

290
00:34:04,000 --> 00:34:12,000
One of which was Alpha Delta Phi, which was one of the most exclusive fraternities on the campus.

291
00:34:12,000 --> 00:34:15,000
They had had no black people in their history.

292
00:34:15,000 --> 00:34:20,000
And so the other one that I narrowed it down to was the Theta Delta Chi.

293
00:34:20,000 --> 00:34:27,000
And of course, they were playing the race card in the other way because they said they don't want you for any other reason that you're black.

294
00:34:27,000 --> 00:34:32,000
And I said, OK, well, I'm going to go away. I feel most comfortable.

295
00:34:32,000 --> 00:34:34,000
And that had to do with who were my friends who were going.

296
00:34:34,000 --> 00:34:37,000
And all the kinds of things guys used to do.

297
00:34:37,000 --> 00:34:41,000
So I got a bit to go to AD and that's where I went.

298
00:34:41,000 --> 00:34:45,000
So I had that reputation of being the first.

299
00:34:45,000 --> 00:34:56,000
And I would say that was probably the mix of what I was involved with at most times.

300
00:34:56,000 --> 00:35:03,000
The mix being those people who I genuinely could get along with and who genuinely like me,

301
00:35:03,000 --> 00:35:08,000
versus the opportunities to be the first wherein you really don't know what's going to happen to you

302
00:35:08,000 --> 00:35:13,000
because you don't know what folks motive underneath all of that.

303
00:35:13,000 --> 00:35:20,000
It was kind of like going, I imagine what it was like going to school and Arkansas for the first time.

304
00:35:20,000 --> 00:35:28,000
The Little Roth Nine, except that there was a more pleasant face to the racism in some cases.

305
00:35:28,000 --> 00:35:32,000
But in case of Alpha Delta Phi, it was great.

306
00:35:32,000 --> 00:35:36,000
I mean, the guys were wonderful. They were welcome to me.

307
00:35:36,000 --> 00:35:42,000
Except for two people, maybe three, that I kind of stayed away from.

308
00:35:42,000 --> 00:35:47,000
Most of the people, if they had any ill feelings, they didn't show it.

309
00:35:47,000 --> 00:35:50,000
I fit in with them and they didn't with me.

310
00:35:50,000 --> 00:35:55,000
Well, ask about how you got connected there in Massachusetts to SNCC in a minute,

311
00:35:55,000 --> 00:35:59,000
but it's not well as possible.

312
00:35:59,000 --> 00:36:02,000
How about the academic experience?

313
00:36:02,000 --> 00:36:06,000
Academics was rough.

314
00:36:06,000 --> 00:36:14,000
I found out later that the schools in the South in general, not just the black schools,

315
00:36:14,000 --> 00:36:24,000
the schools in the South in general, just didn't have what was on the plates of the schools in the North.

316
00:36:24,000 --> 00:36:28,000
For example, I didn't have any calculus. I didn't have any pre-calculus.

317
00:36:28,000 --> 00:36:34,000
The most I had was trigonometry. The guys I was in school with had already had calculus.

318
00:36:34,000 --> 00:36:38,000
I didn't know what calculus was. I still don't know what calculus is if you ask me now.

319
00:36:38,000 --> 00:36:41,000
But I made it through with a C.

320
00:36:41,000 --> 00:36:46,000
Now, that to me was a major hurdle in my life.

321
00:36:46,000 --> 00:36:51,000
A, I had never made a C in my life before.

322
00:36:51,000 --> 00:36:56,000
And most of what I made in that first year, because of calculus and because of physics,

323
00:36:56,000 --> 00:36:59,000
which was based on the same calculus, which I still didn't know,

324
00:36:59,000 --> 00:37:06,000
that pulled away my time to study the English and the French and the history and all that.

325
00:37:06,000 --> 00:37:10,000
I just didn't have time to do it because I was scrambling trying to get that math.

326
00:37:11,000 --> 00:37:15,000
So I ended up with a C average, but I didn't give it a lower C.

327
00:37:15,000 --> 00:37:19,000
I had no Ds. I never had a D on my transcript.

328
00:37:19,000 --> 00:37:28,000
But of course, that kind of ruined my, my, my, my, my, my, the possibilities of me getting really, really, really, really high grade average

329
00:37:28,000 --> 00:37:35,000
because for two semesters, I had two courses, four credits, each set sixteen credits,

330
00:37:35,000 --> 00:37:37,000
over C of one kind or another.

331
00:37:37,000 --> 00:37:44,000
I don't even know if it was a solid C, but it was in that C range, 75, 74, whatever it was.

332
00:37:44,000 --> 00:37:51,000
So my grades suffered and my ego suffered because I thought I was dumb.

333
00:37:51,000 --> 00:37:58,000
I thought I wasn't able to learn because I just couldn't catch on to some of the stuff that was done.

334
00:37:58,000 --> 00:38:07,000
At one point in my second semester, the, I had a math professor named Bailey Brown.

335
00:38:07,000 --> 00:38:12,000
And Professor Brown gave a midterm exam in calculus.

336
00:38:12,000 --> 00:38:19,000
And I had written the answer and I looked at it and then I just exited out and put something else down.

337
00:38:19,000 --> 00:38:23,000
So he went over my paper and he looked at it and said,

338
00:38:23,000 --> 00:38:29,000
you had the right answer and gave me an A.

339
00:38:29,000 --> 00:38:37,000
Because I had it, I just did not have the confidence in myself to know that I had actually understood it to put it down on the paper.

340
00:38:37,000 --> 00:38:44,000
So I went around campus telling everybody, ooh, I got an A in calculus, everybody's, ah, junior's got an A in calculus.

341
00:38:44,000 --> 00:38:48,000
So we celebrated that for a minute until it was time to go into something else.

342
00:38:48,000 --> 00:38:58,000
And then in the final exam, I had three exams in two days, physics, calculus, and history.

343
00:38:58,000 --> 00:39:04,000
I think two in one day of one was on the third and I fell asleep and I couldn't study for the calculus.

344
00:39:04,000 --> 00:39:08,000
So I ended up failing the exam.

345
00:39:08,000 --> 00:39:15,000
So an A plus an F gives you what? A C. I couldn't get away from that C no matter what.

346
00:39:15,000 --> 00:39:18,000
How well I had done, I ended up falling down.

347
00:39:18,000 --> 00:39:25,000
But finally when I got out of my freshman year and my sophomore year, I began to get some Bs along with some Cs.

348
00:39:25,000 --> 00:39:31,000
Junior year, more Bs. And until my senior year, I got Bs and As.

349
00:39:31,000 --> 00:39:35,000
Because I was into some areas that I felt better with and I had more confidence.

350
00:39:35,000 --> 00:39:39,000
I got into political science, for example.

351
00:39:39,000 --> 00:39:44,000
I took economics from a professor who won economics school.

352
00:39:44,000 --> 00:39:47,000
The first economics school I took I got a C plus in it.

353
00:39:47,000 --> 00:39:53,000
But then I met, I heard about this man named Colston Warne, professor Warren.

354
00:39:53,000 --> 00:40:01,000
And because of my work in the movement in 1964, I worked in Harlem.

355
00:40:01,000 --> 00:40:10,000
And I was there with Julian T. Houston and some other people whose names will come back to me.

356
00:40:10,000 --> 00:40:18,000
But Julian T. Houston and Pigeon, Norman Cousins, Norman Cousins daughter.

357
00:40:18,000 --> 00:40:22,000
I can't take them anything else right now, but Pigeon. That was a nickname.

358
00:40:22,000 --> 00:40:30,000
So we were always discussing the civil rights movement, but these young people knew the whole movement.

359
00:40:30,000 --> 00:40:37,000
The whole Marxist context, which was up to that point and an aftermath to me,

360
00:40:37,000 --> 00:40:41,000
because Marxism was something you automatically against.

361
00:40:41,000 --> 00:40:45,000
You didn't think about Karl Marx's anything genuine or good.

362
00:40:45,000 --> 00:40:51,000
But these kids, they understood it. They weren't Marxists, but they understood Marxist analysis.

363
00:40:51,000 --> 00:40:55,000
And so they were applying that to the civil rights movement.

364
00:40:55,000 --> 00:40:59,000
And I couldn't keep up. So I said I better go back and find out something.

365
00:40:59,000 --> 00:41:06,000
I went into Colston Warne's course. And of course, he explained a lot of things that I just didn't know.

366
00:41:06,000 --> 00:41:09,000
So I got an end at Colston.

367
00:41:09,000 --> 00:41:20,000
And that was the first time that I read anything by Karl Marx, but I also read all the other great economic treatises that I hadn't read in economics one, which was just about supply and demand.

368
00:41:20,000 --> 00:41:25,000
So I knew about capitalism, I knew about Marxism, I knew about socialism.

369
00:41:25,000 --> 00:41:33,000
That was probably the best course that I had in terms of opening my eyes to see the world as other people see it.

370
00:41:33,000 --> 00:41:38,000
And in terms, how they valued and judge what we were doing here.

371
00:41:38,000 --> 00:41:41,000
And it introduced me to the whole concept of class.

372
00:41:41,000 --> 00:41:44,000
Because up to that point, I had only been dealing with race.

373
00:41:44,000 --> 00:41:47,000
Everything was race. Things were wrong because of race.

374
00:41:47,000 --> 00:41:51,000
But these kids introduced me, well, you know, you got to do the class analysis too.

375
00:41:51,000 --> 00:42:01,000
So once I had that, the tool that I got from Amherst to Professor Warren, I was able to see the whole situation in another set of glasses.

376
00:42:01,000 --> 00:42:06,000
How did you first get formally connected, so to speak, with SNCC and Amherst?

377
00:42:06,000 --> 00:42:12,000
Well, we were friends of SNCC. We were friends of all civil rights groups, but especially SNCC, because they were our age.

378
00:42:12,000 --> 00:42:23,000
So I was in charge of a group called SRE, there's another story there. Somebody wrote an article in the Amherst paper, the Amherst student.

379
00:42:23,000 --> 00:42:30,000
And didn't sign his name to it. He was decrying the civil rights tactics and the civil rights cause.

380
00:42:30,000 --> 00:42:34,000
So I took him on in an editorial.

381
00:42:34,000 --> 00:42:44,000
And not only did I shut him up, but I got praised from my English teacher who at one point thought everything I wrote was just crap.

382
00:42:44,000 --> 00:42:50,000
But he wrote me and told me that was a great example of understated emotion.

383
00:42:50,000 --> 00:42:55,000
I'm proud of you, your credit to your race, and you know how to write.

384
00:42:55,000 --> 00:43:02,000
That was the best thing I had ever gotten from a teacher up to that point.

385
00:43:02,000 --> 00:43:12,000
I lost that letter, but that's what he said. So after that, my name kind of became synonymous with civil rights.

386
00:43:12,000 --> 00:43:24,000
So they made on campus. So they made me president of the civil rights group, which was called SRE student for racial equality.

387
00:43:24,000 --> 00:43:35,000
So the students for racial equality did demonstrations. We had silent visuals on campus.

388
00:43:35,000 --> 00:43:42,000
And we raised money for a for SNCC and other people who went jail.

389
00:43:42,000 --> 00:43:50,000
I remember one time this, Nick Friedham saying this came over and sang at Smith College.

390
00:43:50,000 --> 00:43:54,000
So I went over to hear him. I met him.

391
00:43:54,000 --> 00:43:57,000
Cordell Reagon became a friend of mine.

392
00:43:57,000 --> 00:44:01,000
Merboh Harrington was at Smith College.

393
00:44:01,000 --> 00:44:06,000
He met, she met Cordell at the same time, and they were eventually married.

394
00:44:06,000 --> 00:44:11,000
That was Cordell's second wife.

395
00:44:11,000 --> 00:44:14,000
Because of that same, I guess it was the same day.

396
00:44:14,000 --> 00:44:18,000
So we all stayed in touch with each other that way.

397
00:44:18,000 --> 00:44:24,000
People were coming up from the south with the stories about what was happening.

398
00:44:24,000 --> 00:44:28,000
And we let them stay in my house. I stayed in fraternity house at by this time.

399
00:44:28,000 --> 00:44:31,000
So that's how I got familiar with SNCC.

400
00:44:31,000 --> 00:44:37,000
So your fraternity house, just for one small side, your fraternity house was okay with black subrides.

401
00:44:37,000 --> 00:44:41,000
They stayed in my room. They didn't care.

402
00:44:41,000 --> 00:44:45,000
So when did you first, I want to ask about the conference,

403
00:44:45,000 --> 00:44:50,000
but that was a major undertaking. When the first comes out to do some work?

404
00:44:50,000 --> 00:44:52,000
Because you mentioned Harlem in 64.

405
00:44:52,000 --> 00:44:59,000
Well, the first work I did was in Richmond in 1962.

406
00:44:59,000 --> 00:45:04,000
I guess it was. I was in 1963.

407
00:45:04,000 --> 00:45:08,000
I was in a demonstration with one of my childhood friends, Brenda Blake,

408
00:45:08,000 --> 00:45:14,000
and charge of the NAACP Youth Group, which was called the Commandos, I think.

409
00:45:14,000 --> 00:45:19,000
Excuse me. That was a hip name for young people at that time.

410
00:45:19,000 --> 00:45:25,000
So I was in a, on a picket line in front of the state house in Richmond.

411
00:45:25,000 --> 00:45:27,000
And there was this guy sitting in the forward.

412
00:45:27,000 --> 00:45:31,000
I'll never forget this, this fat guy got out of the camera and took,

413
00:45:31,000 --> 00:45:35,000
with a camera and just deliberately took everybody's picture on that picket line.

414
00:45:35,000 --> 00:45:42,000
And we knew who he was. He was a man from some level of government that was meant to intimidate us,

415
00:45:42,000 --> 00:45:45,000
which he did. He made his point.

416
00:45:45,000 --> 00:45:51,000
Then the next summer I did voter registration, I think it was within WCP.

417
00:45:51,000 --> 00:45:55,000
Well, maybe it wasn't the next summer, it was the next spring vacation when I came home from Amherst.

418
00:45:55,000 --> 00:45:58,000
I did voter registration.

419
00:45:58,000 --> 00:46:07,000
I did voter registration in Springfield, Massachusetts during another break or kind of another,

420
00:46:07,000 --> 00:46:09,000
maybe just on the weekend.

421
00:46:09,000 --> 00:46:15,000
And that was the extent of my direct action up to that point.

422
00:46:15,000 --> 00:46:19,000
No trip to Atlanta, you had the SNCC folks down there for a music, yeah.

423
00:46:19,000 --> 00:46:24,000
No, hadn't gone to Atlanta. I just knew who the SNCC people were through the SNCC folklore.

424
00:46:24,000 --> 00:46:29,000
You attended March on Washington?

425
00:46:29,000 --> 00:46:37,000
Yes. I had met Marian Wright Edelman, Elliman, up at Amherst. She came to speak.

426
00:46:37,000 --> 00:46:39,000
I guess she would have still been Marian Wright Edelman at that point.

427
00:46:39,000 --> 00:46:49,000
She was Marian Wright Edelman, yes. And she was a vibrant, young, black woman lawyer who had worked in Mississippi,

428
00:46:49,000 --> 00:46:54,000
been in the movement. And that's what she was there to talk about.

429
00:46:54,000 --> 00:47:01,000
But afterwards, me being one of the only blacks on campus, they asked me to go to the president's house to meet her.

430
00:47:01,000 --> 00:47:06,000
So I wasn't met her, we started talking. And she had mentioned something about Operation Crossroads Africa.

431
00:47:06,000 --> 00:47:11,000
I said, what's that all about? So she asked me, we talked a little bit about that.

432
00:47:11,000 --> 00:47:18,000
Operation Crossroads Africa's group sending people over to different countries in Africa to engage in some kind of civil pride.

433
00:47:18,000 --> 00:47:25,000
She asked me if I was interested. I said, yeah, but I don't have any money. She said, don't worry about it.

434
00:47:25,000 --> 00:47:30,000
So within days I heard from Operation Crossroads Africa, and eventually I had a scholarship.

435
00:47:30,000 --> 00:47:40,000
They sent me to Uganda, where I stayed 10 weeks in a tent up in the Kigezi District.

436
00:47:41,000 --> 00:47:48,000
Lots of adventures. We built a hospital, extension to an already existing hospital.

437
00:47:48,000 --> 00:47:54,000
And we did it with bricks, so we helped them make the bricks. We carried the bricks.

438
00:47:54,000 --> 00:48:02,000
We laid some of the bricks except on the corners they had technical students from Uganda who knew how to do the corners,

439
00:48:02,000 --> 00:48:09,000
because we couldn't do the corners. And so coming back from that stay,

440
00:48:09,000 --> 00:48:17,000
I landed in New York, unmanotes to me, on the day of March on Washington.

441
00:48:17,000 --> 00:48:26,000
It's early in the morning, my mother drove to Washington to be with her friend, Charlotte Nash, who had grew up together.

442
00:48:26,000 --> 00:48:31,000
And no, Charlotte lived in Washington. She was bringing Charlotte back, I believe.

443
00:48:31,000 --> 00:48:34,000
Charlotte had come out to meet me and was in New York with her.

444
00:48:35,000 --> 00:48:42,000
Maybe they drove up together and came out, I don't know how it was, but they were together as they off times were at that time.

445
00:48:42,000 --> 00:48:47,000
So she said, oh, and there's March on Washington, I said, what?

446
00:48:47,000 --> 00:48:53,000
I said, I want to go. So Johnny and I, my brother and I, she dropped us off on some corner, told us to meet us somewhere else,

447
00:48:53,000 --> 00:48:58,000
laid on in the evening, which we did. And so for the whole day, we were there.

448
00:48:58,000 --> 00:49:03,000
And we saw, and we learned, and I wanted to be a part of it.

449
00:49:03,000 --> 00:49:08,000
I don't think Johnny wanted to be a part of it as much as I did, but I certainly did.

450
00:49:08,000 --> 00:49:14,000
And the SNCC kids were the ones that blew my mind, because they were singing all the most recent songs from Danville.

451
00:49:14,000 --> 00:49:24,000
And ironically, I had seen an old newspaper while I was in, I was in, Kigaisy District in Uganda.

452
00:49:24,000 --> 00:49:33,000
And it was an old newspaper, I guess it was a London Times or New York Times or something, and I had a picture of what was happening.

453
00:49:33,000 --> 00:49:42,000
You know, the violence in 1963 earlier that summer. And this was, of course, maybe a month later, when I saw it, I said, man, I should have been there.

454
00:49:42,000 --> 00:49:45,000
Because if I had been in home, I'd have been there.

455
00:49:46,000 --> 00:49:51,000
So that's how I, that was my introduction to SNCC, all those little pieces.

456
00:49:51,000 --> 00:49:56,000
And of course, Charles Sherrod's people, they became a part of SNCC.

457
00:49:56,000 --> 00:50:03,000
That's when SNCC formed and, and Raleigh that same year. So that's what, that's what that was all about.

458
00:50:03,000 --> 00:50:14,000
Yeah. I wouldn't, I wouldn't guess, and say that day at March on Washington, you would not have already been a tenant to these tensions emerging in the movement between, say,

459
00:50:14,000 --> 00:50:20,000
you know, Kingsfaction and the younger folks who would get John Lewis and SNCC and we're getting pretty frustrated.

460
00:50:20,000 --> 00:50:27,000
Not at that time. I've read about it and talked about it and people have told me things about it since then.

461
00:50:27,000 --> 00:50:39,000
Tell me a little bit more about, about in mid-February of 1965, you, you convened and organized a very, very large conference, as you've mentioned earlier, on the campus.

462
00:50:40,000 --> 00:50:46,000
I'm going to talk about the conference.

463
00:50:46,000 --> 00:50:49,000
Okay, we're back on after a break of the few minutes.

464
00:50:49,000 --> 00:50:56,000
I had, and it's Malcolm X, I blank on those names sometimes.

465
00:50:56,000 --> 00:50:57,000
Michael Harrington?

466
00:50:57,000 --> 00:51:03,000
Michael Harrington and Ossie Davis. I always blank on his name. Michael Harrington, Michael Harrington.

467
00:51:03,000 --> 00:51:05,000
I don't know why.

468
00:51:05,000 --> 00:51:13,000
Let me say, it sounds as if you were a pretty ambitious young man to contemplate a conference of this scope and scale.

469
00:51:13,000 --> 00:51:18,000
Can you talk about how it all came to be?

470
00:51:18,000 --> 00:51:26,000
Well, I guess we would try to do individuals on the campus.

471
00:51:27,000 --> 00:51:33,000
This is a big break, I understand you have this big one right here.

472
00:51:33,000 --> 00:51:47,000
We knew from the buzz around the Civil Rights College Circuit that there was disagreement about the directions in Civil Rights.

473
00:51:48,000 --> 00:52:05,000
There was black nationalism as identified and promoted by Malcolm X, which had not really come into the common day lexicon of most students, certainly not in mind.

474
00:52:05,000 --> 00:52:12,000
But there was something terribly thrilling about Malcolm X, from what I had seen and heard.

475
00:52:13,000 --> 00:52:24,000
I hadn't met any of the people who really knew him well as I was subsequently to meet such as Percy Sutton, who became a friend of mine, who was Malcolm X's lawyer.

476
00:52:24,000 --> 00:52:37,000
I hadn't talked to any of the people who vilified him, but I knew there must be some reason why this man was getting vilified so much on television on a daily basis sometimes.

477
00:52:37,000 --> 00:52:43,000
I hate that he produced, well I wanted to see for myself and the rest of us there too.

478
00:52:43,000 --> 00:52:54,000
Ossie Davis, we chose because someone knew he had a great civil rights record, he was not just an ordinary actor.

479
00:52:54,000 --> 00:53:01,000
Michael Harrington, because he was the man that they said, quote unquote, discovered poverty.

480
00:53:01,000 --> 00:53:04,000
He was a prolific writer.

481
00:53:04,000 --> 00:53:10,000
So this little committee of Oz knew these people or knew of these people.

482
00:53:10,000 --> 00:53:13,000
We said we're going to really have this.

483
00:53:13,000 --> 00:53:18,000
The opening session is going to set the tone for the rest of the convention.

484
00:53:18,000 --> 00:53:22,000
Civil rights, movement, reform or revolution.

485
00:53:22,000 --> 00:53:29,000
So I got Malcolm X's home number from somebody I knew, again it was the network.

486
00:53:29,000 --> 00:53:36,000
So I called him up. He entered the phone and I said no.

487
00:53:36,000 --> 00:53:37,000
You're 22 years old?

488
00:53:37,000 --> 00:53:38,000
I was in 22.

489
00:53:38,000 --> 00:53:43,000
This was in, we were planning for this thing, so I was 20.

490
00:53:43,000 --> 00:53:47,000
I was probably 20 years old when this thing was being planned.

491
00:53:47,000 --> 00:53:53,000
So maybe 20 or just, no.

492
00:53:53,000 --> 00:53:54,000
I don't know.

493
00:53:54,000 --> 00:53:55,000
20 or 21.

494
00:53:55,000 --> 00:53:57,000
One of those doesn't matter.

495
00:53:57,000 --> 00:53:59,000
You're right.

496
00:53:59,000 --> 00:54:00,000
I was a young kid.

497
00:54:00,000 --> 00:54:02,000
So I called him up.

498
00:54:02,000 --> 00:54:04,000
He entered the phone.

499
00:54:04,000 --> 00:54:14,000
I said wow, I'm talking to Malcolm X and I explained what I wanted and he said well what kind of honorarium do you have?

500
00:54:14,000 --> 00:54:22,000
I think I told him $1,000 and he thought for a minute that's not very much money.

501
00:54:22,000 --> 00:54:24,000
And he thought for some more.

502
00:54:24,000 --> 00:54:32,000
I think I may have explained that this was important because we wanted to explain just what these are,

503
00:54:32,000 --> 00:54:40,000
the emerging ideas that were coming out of the American culture, especially from Black folks, something like that.

504
00:54:40,000 --> 00:54:44,000
I must have said something because he said okay, I'll do it.

505
00:54:44,000 --> 00:54:50,000
I said wow, I put the phone down and it was a public phone somewhere on campus.

506
00:54:50,000 --> 00:54:52,000
We didn't have phones in our rooms.

507
00:54:52,000 --> 00:55:04,000
This was all done at a bell telephone with me standing there at the wall, on a wall, not even in a booth talking to Malcolm X.

508
00:55:04,000 --> 00:55:08,000
I hadn't even thought about that before because I had another strange experience like that.

509
00:55:08,000 --> 00:55:14,000
But anyway, involving trying to get a date with guys just looking over your shoulder.

510
00:55:14,000 --> 00:55:18,000
You're standing there with this big phone on a wall and you're sitting there talking to me.

511
00:55:18,000 --> 00:55:23,000
Well you don't know me but my name is so intense and I was wondering if you'd like to go out with it tonight.

512
00:55:23,000 --> 00:55:29,000
Similarly, transfer that whole experience up at a notch, several nights.

513
00:55:29,000 --> 00:55:33,000
I was speaking to Malcolm X and he says he's going to come.

514
00:55:33,000 --> 00:55:35,000
I went back and told a group everything.

515
00:55:35,000 --> 00:55:36,000
Wow.

516
00:55:36,000 --> 00:55:41,000
We had similar experiences with whoever called, Ossie Davis, whoever called Harrington.

517
00:55:41,000 --> 00:55:45,000
I didn't do those two and they all said they would come.

518
00:55:45,000 --> 00:55:52,000
Then we had to fill in for our ordinary little breakout sessions.

519
00:55:52,000 --> 00:55:58,000
For our quote unquote ordinary breakout sessions, we had all the civil rights luminaries that were coming out.

520
00:55:58,000 --> 00:56:01,000
The ordinary is that we could find.

521
00:56:01,000 --> 00:56:09,000
The people who were in the trenches, mostly in the south, but some in the north as well.

522
00:56:09,000 --> 00:56:13,000
I still have that poster.

523
00:56:13,000 --> 00:56:23,000
We had people who were in core, people who were in SNCC, people who were in northern student movement,

524
00:56:23,000 --> 00:56:30,000
all of the groups that were doing anything on the cutting edge anywhere and they all said they would come.

525
00:56:30,000 --> 00:56:42,000
They all did come except Malcolm X was in France when extra day trying to get into England or out of England into France.

526
00:56:42,000 --> 00:56:45,000
One of those and they wouldn't let him in until he lost the day.

527
00:56:45,000 --> 00:56:52,000
I got a call from one of his people saying I'm sorry Mr. Williams, but he's not going to be able to be there.

528
00:56:52,000 --> 00:56:57,000
He really wanted to come and I really believe he did.

529
00:56:57,000 --> 00:57:00,000
So I was down to two.

530
00:57:00,000 --> 00:57:07,000
So then that day of the conference which was the Friday, I think February 12, 1965.

531
00:57:07,000 --> 00:57:14,000
I got word from Michael Harrington, he couldn't make it because of an ice storm in New York.

532
00:57:14,000 --> 00:57:20,000
So I said oh my god, we're going to have a thousand people hanging from the raptors in Mount Holyoke

533
00:57:20,000 --> 00:57:25,000
and they're not going to come there to see me. I was cheering it. I was them seeing it.

534
00:57:25,000 --> 00:57:30,000
But Ossie Davis came through because he had left the day earlier.

535
00:57:30,000 --> 00:57:33,000
Got ahead of the storm some kind of way.

536
00:57:33,000 --> 00:57:36,000
So he came and I explained the situation to him.

537
00:57:36,000 --> 00:57:41,000
I said Malcolm can't come, blah blah blah. Michael Harrington can't come.

538
00:57:41,000 --> 00:57:43,000
So he said that's okay.

539
00:57:43,000 --> 00:57:48,000
I'll talk about what they would have talked about and then I'll talk about what I wanted to talk about.

540
00:57:48,000 --> 00:57:56,000
And because he was the consul, he was the consulment actor that he was, he put himself into each role.

541
00:57:56,000 --> 00:58:03,000
And because he was very knowledgeable about who they were, he pulled it off.

542
00:58:03,000 --> 00:58:06,000
Got to stand in ovation. We got a standing ovation.

543
00:58:06,000 --> 00:58:11,000
We got the legitimacy we needed because you know these colleges had put some money to this thing.

544
00:58:11,000 --> 00:58:16,000
And they didn't want to see me up on the stage either holding my hand talking about I couldn't get in there.

545
00:58:16,000 --> 00:58:19,000
And the conference just flowed from there.

546
00:58:19,000 --> 00:58:22,000
I mean it was just just just a big success.

547
00:58:22,000 --> 00:58:27,000
I met a lot of people that day that I hadn't met before.

548
00:58:27,000 --> 00:58:32,000
People who were who were just folks I had heard about but hadn't really met.

549
00:58:32,000 --> 00:58:36,000
Got some more intelligence about what was going on especially in the south.

550
00:58:36,000 --> 00:58:39,000
But also in places like Harlem.

551
00:58:39,000 --> 00:58:41,000
So it was really good.

552
00:58:41,000 --> 00:58:47,000
What was your perspective around that weekend of that conference on the question of reform versus revolution?

553
00:58:47,000 --> 00:58:50,000
Revolution. I was becoming a revolutionary.

554
00:58:50,000 --> 00:58:55,000
I mean I was listening to all of those other pieces. I didn't know that much about it.

555
00:58:55,000 --> 00:59:00,000
I didn't, for example, I told you I didn't know the class aspect of what was going on.

556
00:59:00,000 --> 00:59:04,000
But this was no reform process. I could see this was going to change people's lives forever.

557
00:59:04,000 --> 00:59:06,000
And it was going to change America forever.

558
00:59:06,000 --> 00:59:10,000
If we got what we demanded and we were intent on getting what we demanded,

559
00:59:10,000 --> 00:59:14,000
this was going to change the institutions in America forever.

560
00:59:14,000 --> 00:59:18,000
And to a certain extent it did.

561
00:59:18,000 --> 00:59:21,000
Nothing extra was killed.

562
00:59:21,000 --> 00:59:22,000
Are we playing it?

563
00:59:22,000 --> 00:59:24,000
Yes. That's Sunday, 21st.

564
00:59:24,000 --> 00:59:30,000
And I always wonder would somebody have tried to kill him in Massachusetts?

565
00:59:30,000 --> 00:59:35,000
Because you certainly had an overwhelming escape in all of those woods and all of those woods.

566
00:59:35,000 --> 00:59:44,000
And all of those hills just coming up the hills, winding your way to South Hadley as mountains,

567
00:59:44,000 --> 00:59:47,000
not mountains like out west.

568
00:59:47,000 --> 00:59:53,000
Certainly steep hills and very lonely and too late in highways and stuff like that.

569
00:59:53,000 --> 01:00:03,000
I said to myself, I wonder if somebody would have tried to get him there as opposed to when they actually did get him in the Autobahn Ballroom a week later.

570
01:00:04,000 --> 01:00:07,000
So chilling thought.

571
01:00:07,000 --> 01:00:10,000
Do you remember your reaction?

572
01:00:10,000 --> 01:00:12,000
To Malcolm's death?

573
01:00:12,000 --> 01:00:21,000
Absolute anger, sadness, grief, regret that I hadn't really had a chance to meet him just at one conversation.

574
01:00:21,000 --> 01:00:23,000
Because I knew I would have liked him.

575
01:00:23,000 --> 01:00:32,000
Just from the conversation, I liked the sound of his voice and the intensity and the honesty that was there.

576
01:00:32,000 --> 01:00:37,000
He really cared about me and this conference.

577
01:00:37,000 --> 01:00:41,000
That's why he agreed to come for so little money.

578
01:00:41,000 --> 01:00:48,000
Not many weeks later you went to Alabama.

579
01:00:48,000 --> 01:00:51,000
Right. That was February.

580
01:00:51,000 --> 01:00:59,000
And in March, the same little group decided we were going to go to the Selma to Montgomery March and March.

581
01:00:59,000 --> 01:01:01,000
We were kind of like done, where we've done this.

582
01:01:01,000 --> 01:01:05,000
We went from visuals to a magnificent conference.

583
01:01:05,000 --> 01:01:06,000
Where can we go next?

584
01:01:06,000 --> 01:01:08,000
Where we got to go south.

585
01:01:08,000 --> 01:01:10,000
It was time for our manifest destiny.

586
01:01:10,000 --> 01:01:12,000
We had been beating around the bush.

587
01:01:12,000 --> 01:01:21,000
And I had been to Harlem this summer before to work with my childhood friend, Julian Houston,

588
01:01:21,000 --> 01:01:27,000
who is now a retired judge in Massachusetts.

589
01:01:27,000 --> 01:01:37,000
But he was on one of those projects called the Harlem Education Program, which was associated with the Northern Student Movement.

590
01:01:37,000 --> 01:01:47,000
So I hadn't had that experience, but I hadn't had the front line experience that only the south could bring.

591
01:01:47,000 --> 01:01:48,000
And none of us had.

592
01:01:48,000 --> 01:01:49,000
Because we'd all been in college.

593
01:01:49,000 --> 01:01:51,000
We'd all decided to stay in college.

594
01:01:51,000 --> 01:02:00,000
We were committed to the revolution, but you can't really be a revolutionary until you go to the front line.

595
01:02:00,000 --> 01:02:01,000
So that's what we did.

596
01:02:01,000 --> 01:02:17,000
We piled into a Volkswagen bus, about seven of us, from UMass, University of Massachusetts, from Mount Holyoke, from Smith and from Amherst.

597
01:02:17,000 --> 01:02:19,000
And we went on our way.

598
01:02:19,000 --> 01:02:28,000
So we stopped at my mother and father's house in Richmond just to stop in and get fortified along the way.

599
01:02:28,000 --> 01:02:30,000
Because we didn't stop driving.

600
01:02:30,000 --> 01:02:31,000
We weren't going to sleep overnight in the way.

601
01:02:31,000 --> 01:02:35,000
We just rotated drivers.

602
01:02:35,000 --> 01:02:40,000
And my father took a look at that Volkswagen bus.

603
01:02:40,000 --> 01:02:42,000
I think we were having some trouble.

604
01:02:42,000 --> 01:02:45,000
He said, no, no, no, no, no, no, no.

605
01:02:45,000 --> 01:02:47,000
Take my station wagon.

606
01:02:47,000 --> 01:02:53,000
So he gave us his station wagon, which was a big Buick station wagon.

607
01:02:53,000 --> 01:02:55,000
It was full of people, seven.

608
01:02:55,000 --> 01:02:58,000
And we piled luggage in the back.

609
01:02:58,000 --> 01:03:01,000
And we went on our way.

610
01:03:01,000 --> 01:03:07,000
Now, that was fortuitous because in South Carolina.

611
01:03:07,000 --> 01:03:10,000
And by that night, we were in South Carolina.

612
01:03:10,000 --> 01:03:16,000
And the guy named Fred Arano was driving the car.

613
01:03:16,000 --> 01:03:20,000
And he was apparently, because the rest of us were asleep.

614
01:03:20,000 --> 01:03:23,000
He must have kind of followed asleep at the wheel.

615
01:03:23,000 --> 01:03:25,000
And he was going over the highway.

616
01:03:25,000 --> 01:03:27,000
And the cop stopped it.

617
01:03:27,000 --> 01:03:34,000
So the five whites stayed in the middle of the car wherever they were.

618
01:03:34,000 --> 01:03:41,000
And the two of us who were black got in the back seat underneath some clothes and hid.

619
01:03:41,000 --> 01:03:43,000
Because we did not want to be seen.

620
01:03:43,000 --> 01:03:46,000
And we did not want to be caught in an integrated cop car.

621
01:03:46,000 --> 01:03:51,000
So Fred, who was quick on his feet, told the cop,

622
01:03:51,000 --> 01:03:59,000
we were on our way to Florida for the spring break fling that they had down there every year.

623
01:03:59,000 --> 01:04:07,000
Where thousands of white kids get together, get drunk, get laid, and go on back to school.

624
01:04:07,000 --> 01:04:10,000
So he took a look at Fred, said, be careful.

625
01:04:10,000 --> 01:04:11,000
You look out.

626
01:04:11,000 --> 01:04:14,000
You're a little sleepy, but go ahead.

627
01:04:14,000 --> 01:04:19,000
Now, later on, we heard that other integrated cars got stopped.

628
01:04:19,000 --> 01:04:26,000
And they never made it to the march because they were arrested on some trumped up charge in places like South Carolina, wherever we had to go.

629
01:04:26,000 --> 01:04:33,000
So but for Fred's quickness of foot, he said he could have said,

630
01:04:33,000 --> 01:04:36,000
we were on our way to the march.

631
01:04:36,000 --> 01:04:40,000
South righteous, we're on our way to put foot.

632
01:04:40,000 --> 01:04:45,000
What is it? Foot, Lord of the Day, where they had these things, the spring flings.

633
01:04:45,000 --> 01:04:46,000
So we got away.

634
01:04:46,000 --> 01:04:47,000
And we went on down.

635
01:04:47,000 --> 01:04:49,000
Later on, we had an accident.

636
01:04:49,000 --> 01:04:55,000
This big semi-trailer truck plows into my father's car.

637
01:04:55,000 --> 01:04:57,000
I was driving at that point.

638
01:04:57,000 --> 01:05:01,000
Just came then to front fender against the wheel.

639
01:05:01,000 --> 01:05:02,000
We were in one lane.

640
01:05:02,000 --> 01:05:05,000
He was in another lane, and he just turned right into us.

641
01:05:05,000 --> 01:05:09,000
So we had to, the filling station was right there.

642
01:05:09,000 --> 01:05:10,000
The gas station was right there.

643
01:05:10,000 --> 01:05:13,000
We pulled into it as much as we could.

644
01:05:13,000 --> 01:05:16,000
But the bumper was on the wheel.

645
01:05:16,000 --> 01:05:19,000
You couldn't drive.

646
01:05:19,000 --> 01:05:24,000
So I don't know why this guy, I mean the guy,

647
01:05:24,000 --> 01:05:28,000
these young guys in the gas station didn't seem to mind,

648
01:05:28,000 --> 01:05:31,000
this was an integrated group.

649
01:05:31,000 --> 01:05:33,000
In the K-Way we were going.

650
01:05:33,000 --> 01:05:34,000
He just fixed the car.

651
01:05:34,000 --> 01:05:35,000
He just pulled it off.

652
01:05:35,000 --> 01:05:37,000
We got some gas, and got the hell out of it,

653
01:05:37,000 --> 01:05:40,000
because it was in some little town in Georgia.

654
01:05:40,000 --> 01:05:42,000
So we kept going.

655
01:05:42,000 --> 01:05:44,000
And finally got to Montgomery.

656
01:05:44,000 --> 01:05:49,000
They had told us to check in with the SNCC office before going to Selma,

657
01:05:49,000 --> 01:05:53,000
because you want to find out if the clan had been operating

658
01:05:53,000 --> 01:05:57,000
along whatever that was at that particular time.

659
01:05:57,000 --> 01:06:03,000
They were always operating, but you wanted to find out if there was a heightened watch or not.

660
01:06:03,000 --> 01:06:09,000
And we went upstairs on the second floor, corner of Jackson and High Street in Montgomery,

661
01:06:09,000 --> 01:06:12,000
which is where the SNCC office was.

662
01:06:12,000 --> 01:06:15,000
And there were various SNCC operatives there, I don't know who they were,

663
01:06:15,000 --> 01:06:17,000
who they all were.

664
01:06:17,000 --> 01:06:20,000
Only when I recognized was Stokely Carmichael Carmichael.

665
01:06:20,000 --> 01:06:24,000
And he said, what the hell are you going to sell my phone?

666
01:06:24,000 --> 01:06:26,000
We need you here at Montgomery.

667
01:06:26,000 --> 01:06:30,000
And then he explained that they were doing a parallel operation,

668
01:06:30,000 --> 01:06:33,000
because they didn't trust King and SCLC.

669
01:06:33,000 --> 01:06:37,000
We didn't want to get sold out on this voter rights.

670
01:06:37,000 --> 01:06:43,000
So they were running a separate operation in Montgomery.

671
01:06:43,000 --> 01:06:49,000
Now, as I looked back into the how the march unfolded,

672
01:06:49,000 --> 01:06:53,000
I didn't know at the time that this was a SNCC idea to begin with,

673
01:06:53,000 --> 01:07:03,000
because Jimmie Lee Jackson had been killed in some little town on the other side of the bridge,

674
01:07:03,000 --> 01:07:05,000
days before.

675
01:07:05,000 --> 01:07:07,000
And so the people were mad and said they were on the march.

676
01:07:07,000 --> 01:07:14,000
And John Lewis led that march, and there's a famous picture of him being beat down.

677
01:07:14,000 --> 01:07:18,000
That was before SCLC and King were involved.

678
01:07:18,000 --> 01:07:22,000
King, I also found out, didn't want to get involved,

679
01:07:22,000 --> 01:07:27,000
but his people were telling him you got to get in front of this march.

680
01:07:27,000 --> 01:07:32,000
He didn't want to do it because the law, quote unquote,

681
01:07:32,000 --> 01:07:35,000
was not on outside at that point.

682
01:07:35,000 --> 01:07:38,000
There was an injunction, no marches.

683
01:07:38,000 --> 01:07:44,000
But then the people in the United States got involved and pressured Johnson to lift the state.

684
01:07:44,000 --> 01:07:48,000
So Johnson got in touch with the judge apparently, and the judge lifted the state

685
01:07:48,000 --> 01:07:50,000
so the march could go on.

686
01:07:50,000 --> 01:07:54,000
And so that's when it became an SCLC march, as opposed to a SNCC march.

687
01:07:54,000 --> 01:07:57,000
So I'm putting two and two together, nobody told me,

688
01:07:57,000 --> 01:08:02,000
but SNCC was probably mad anyway, because this thing had been taken away.

689
01:08:02,000 --> 01:08:06,000
The third thing I learned from listening, just listening, listening,

690
01:08:06,000 --> 01:08:09,000
was that there was competition from the good guys,

691
01:08:09,000 --> 01:08:13,000
from within the ranks of the good guys.

692
01:08:13,000 --> 01:08:20,000
And so the Montgomery was set up, just like that.

693
01:08:20,000 --> 01:08:23,000
SNCC was able to do that because SNCC was SNCC.

694
01:08:23,000 --> 01:08:26,000
And they had the power to do that.

695
01:08:26,000 --> 01:08:30,000
They could come in and virtually take over the city,

696
01:08:30,000 --> 01:08:36,000
command the attention of the police power with so much so that they could just shut us down,

697
01:08:36,000 --> 01:08:41,000
they had to use all those forces to shut us down at the corner of Jackson and High Street.

698
01:08:41,000 --> 01:08:43,000
They didn't let anybody out.

699
01:08:43,000 --> 01:08:46,000
They were letting people in, though, which was their tactical mistake,

700
01:08:46,000 --> 01:08:49,000
because more and more people were gathering.

701
01:08:49,000 --> 01:08:55,000
And they had hired, or maybe they was volunteers, maybe they see volunteers,

702
01:08:55,000 --> 01:09:01,000
but they had guys from the country coming in on horses with great, big, long sticks,

703
01:09:01,000 --> 01:09:03,000
not your ordinary police billy club.

704
01:09:03,000 --> 01:09:08,000
They were there, too, long sticks, maybe three people wide.

705
01:09:08,000 --> 01:09:15,000
And they used them, they heard the cattle beat the cattle along when they were moving, I guess.

706
01:09:15,000 --> 01:09:21,000
So they were given permission to knock the hell out of us whenever they wanted to.

707
01:09:21,000 --> 01:09:25,000
So every time we tried to march out of their corner of Jackson and High Street,

708
01:09:25,000 --> 01:09:31,000
these guys on horses and the police on motorcycles would beat us down.

709
01:09:31,000 --> 01:09:35,000
I understand these guys were the clan, they had just deputized them for the moment.

710
01:09:35,000 --> 01:09:43,000
I have no confirmation whatsoever, but that was what was the rumor rampant in the street.

711
01:09:43,000 --> 01:09:46,000
But we didn't care who they were, they were trying to knock the hell out of us.

712
01:09:46,000 --> 01:09:50,000
So I was quick enough to stay away from it, from the beating.

713
01:09:50,000 --> 01:09:58,000
There was one time when we were on a little church there in the middle of the block,

714
01:09:58,000 --> 01:10:02,000
where at the beginning of the block, they'd never opened this door to help us.

715
01:10:02,000 --> 01:10:06,000
Never, never, never did that church open.

716
01:10:06,000 --> 01:10:09,000
There were three steps going up to the door.

717
01:10:09,000 --> 01:10:12,000
And we were running from the cops, running from the police.

718
01:10:12,000 --> 01:10:17,000
That was the only place to go, and they had us around it.

719
01:10:17,000 --> 01:10:20,000
And they were about to charge, and somebody started singing,

720
01:10:20,000 --> 01:10:27,000
this may be the last time, it may be the last time, I don't know.

721
01:10:27,000 --> 01:10:31,000
And that song sticks with me to this day because everybody started singing it,

722
01:10:31,000 --> 01:10:36,000
and we were all prepared for whatever might happen.

723
01:10:36,000 --> 01:10:42,000
But their horses stopped, their motorcycle people stopped,

724
01:10:42,000 --> 01:10:48,000
they looked at us, turned around and let us go.

725
01:10:48,000 --> 01:10:54,000
And that was the first time I had any evidence that there was really a guard,

726
01:10:54,000 --> 01:10:58,000
because there was no way we could have stopped them.

727
01:10:58,000 --> 01:11:04,000
But if I were six, seven of us could all come running to escape the inevitable.

728
01:11:04,000 --> 01:11:08,000
And here it was, what it didn't come.

729
01:11:08,000 --> 01:11:11,000
I had to change my mind about God at that point.

730
01:11:11,000 --> 01:11:14,000
I was a member of the church, and I had been baptized,

731
01:11:14,000 --> 01:11:16,000
but I hadn't paid much attention to that.

732
01:11:16,000 --> 01:11:23,000
But from that point forward, I had to really revise my thinking about who was in charge on that street,

733
01:11:23,000 --> 01:11:30,000
because I escaped, a lot of people didn't, I escaped unharmed in terms of physical damage.

734
01:11:30,000 --> 01:11:38,000
Another time I ran from horses into somebody's house, and their door was open.

735
01:11:38,000 --> 01:11:44,000
But the door was so, the door was a regular height door,

736
01:11:44,000 --> 01:11:47,000
and the horse couldn't get in there.

737
01:11:47,000 --> 01:11:50,000
That's the only thing that saved me at that particular time.

738
01:11:50,000 --> 01:11:56,000
And on the television, I saw Lyndon Johnson in front of the Congress,

739
01:11:56,000 --> 01:12:02,000
when he said, we shall overcome, talking about the voter rights of people.

740
01:12:02,000 --> 01:12:06,000
And he made that famous comment about we shall overcome.

741
01:12:06,000 --> 01:12:11,000
And I'm standing there looking at him, and I'm watching what's going on in that street,

742
01:12:11,000 --> 01:12:14,000
and I plunge back out into the dark.

743
01:12:14,000 --> 01:12:19,000
And that was in my mind that this man was a hypocrite.

744
01:12:19,000 --> 01:12:27,000
Another thing that happened during that situation, a Puerto Rican guy.

745
01:12:27,000 --> 01:12:30,000
He was Latino.

746
01:12:30,000 --> 01:12:33,000
I think he was Puerto Rican.

747
01:12:33,000 --> 01:12:37,000
Let me get some more water.

748
01:12:37,000 --> 01:12:43,000
We are back on after a short break.

749
01:12:43,000 --> 01:12:52,000
How long did you arrive in front of the John Lewis march?

750
01:12:52,000 --> 01:12:55,000
No, it was after that.

751
01:12:55,000 --> 01:12:57,000
Oh, this is after that.

752
01:12:57,000 --> 01:13:02,000
Also after the meal and turnaround on the ninth.

753
01:13:02,000 --> 01:13:05,000
Yes.

754
01:13:05,000 --> 01:13:11,000
So you arrived for the march that is scheduled.

755
01:13:11,000 --> 01:13:17,000
So you were there when the marchers arrived?

756
01:13:17,000 --> 01:13:19,000
Never made it to Selma.

757
01:13:19,000 --> 01:13:21,000
No, but when they came to Montgomery.

758
01:13:21,000 --> 01:13:23,000
Oh, yeah.

759
01:13:23,000 --> 01:13:24,000
Yeah, yeah.

760
01:13:24,000 --> 01:13:26,000
But, well, I was and I wasn't.

761
01:13:26,000 --> 01:13:28,000
I was in Kilby Prison State Prison at that time.

762
01:13:28,000 --> 01:13:29,000
You had been arrested by that?

763
01:13:29,000 --> 01:13:30,000
Yeah.

764
01:13:30,000 --> 01:13:31,000
I had been arrested by that.

765
01:13:31,000 --> 01:13:33,000
What were the circumstances of your arrest?

766
01:13:33,000 --> 01:13:38,000
Well, let me tell you this one thing first about the guy with Puerto Rican guy.

767
01:13:38,000 --> 01:13:42,000
The cops came looming through on their motorcycle.

768
01:13:42,000 --> 01:13:48,000
One cop did drove down to the end of the street and he kneeled down in front.

769
01:13:48,000 --> 01:13:53,000
Just as a protest, the guy came and hit him with the motorcycle.

770
01:13:53,000 --> 01:14:01,000
But he was able nimble enough to take the blow on his left thigh and he kind of rolled away.

771
01:14:01,000 --> 01:14:04,000
The motorcycle fell.

772
01:14:04,000 --> 01:14:11,000
The cop was scattered all over the ground and there were no cops around.

773
01:14:11,000 --> 01:14:17,000
The rest of us moved forward to get that cop, me included.

774
01:14:17,000 --> 01:14:19,000
He jumped up.

775
01:14:19,000 --> 01:14:21,000
This was the most brave thing I ever seen.

776
01:14:21,000 --> 01:14:25,000
He jumped up and stopped us because we were supposed to be non-violent.

777
01:14:25,000 --> 01:14:28,000
He reminded us this was non-violent.

778
01:14:28,000 --> 01:14:30,000
We can't do that.

779
01:14:30,000 --> 01:14:36,000
That cop would probably have been severely hurt that day.

780
01:14:36,000 --> 01:14:43,000
And then it would have been a whole different kind of situation because they would have brought in all the police power in the state

781
01:14:43,000 --> 01:14:49,000
and would have snuffed us out because then we would have been terrorist instead of non-violent protestors.

782
01:14:49,000 --> 01:14:51,000
And he was smart enough to do that.

783
01:14:51,000 --> 01:14:53,000
So I always remember him for that.

784
01:14:53,000 --> 01:14:56,000
And he was on one leg because he couldn't move the other leg.

785
01:14:56,000 --> 01:14:58,000
And he stopped that crowd.

786
01:14:58,000 --> 01:15:00,000
You can't do it.

787
01:15:00,000 --> 01:15:02,000
And so we all backed off.

788
01:15:02,000 --> 01:15:04,000
The cop jumped up.

789
01:15:04,000 --> 01:15:07,000
Got that big heavy motorcycle.

790
01:15:07,000 --> 01:15:09,000
Shroom.

791
01:15:09,000 --> 01:15:11,000
And drove on back the way he came from.

792
01:15:11,000 --> 01:15:13,000
Now how did I get arrested?

793
01:15:13,000 --> 01:15:18,000
Several times we tried to march and each time they drove us back.

794
01:15:18,000 --> 01:15:23,000
At one point, King came over because the march had already started.

795
01:15:23,000 --> 01:15:26,000
Somebody told King this thing is getting out of hand.

796
01:15:26,000 --> 01:15:28,000
You better go to my government.

797
01:15:28,000 --> 01:15:31,000
Because now more and more press was coming.

798
01:15:31,000 --> 01:15:35,000
More and more media was coming.

799
01:15:35,000 --> 01:15:41,000
So he came over and amazingly the doors opened and we were going to go.

800
01:15:41,000 --> 01:15:45,000
And I say the doors, I mean the barricades were removed and we marched.

801
01:15:45,000 --> 01:15:50,000
But he only marched us for about two blocks.

802
01:15:50,000 --> 01:15:53,000
And he turned us back around.

803
01:15:53,000 --> 01:15:57,000
And we went back toward the barricades.

804
01:15:57,000 --> 01:16:02,000
And during that time the cops were throwing peanuts at us.

805
01:16:02,000 --> 01:16:03,000
With this grin on their faces.

806
01:16:03,000 --> 01:16:05,000
Though they knew what was going on.

807
01:16:05,000 --> 01:16:06,000
This thing had been planned.

808
01:16:06,000 --> 01:16:12,000
This was supposed to take the edge off our desired march.

809
01:16:12,000 --> 01:16:14,000
Because people weren't going to be satisfied with that.

810
01:16:14,000 --> 01:16:16,000
We were young people.

811
01:16:16,000 --> 01:16:19,000
We weren't going to be satisfied with that.

812
01:16:19,000 --> 01:16:26,000
So that same day or the next day, the SNCC organizers led us through the back door.

813
01:16:26,000 --> 01:16:31,000
So they had didn't have cops down at the other end of the avenue.

814
01:16:31,000 --> 01:16:34,000
We went out the back way very quickly.

815
01:16:34,000 --> 01:16:39,000
We went around the side of Alabama State University.

816
01:16:39,000 --> 01:16:45,000
Went in the school, emptied the school, singing freedom songs.

817
01:16:45,000 --> 01:16:48,000
Emptyed everybody in that school camp.

818
01:16:48,000 --> 01:16:51,000
Some professors tried to stop the kids.

819
01:16:51,000 --> 01:16:55,000
Some of them just stood aside and smiled.

820
01:16:55,000 --> 01:16:59,000
By that time we had doubled in size.

821
01:16:59,000 --> 01:17:06,000
And now I was a mostly black group as opposed to integrated heavily with whites.

822
01:17:06,000 --> 01:17:12,000
Now I was mostly black with all of the energy that that conveys young black men and women.

823
01:17:12,000 --> 01:17:17,000
So then we went back to march again.

824
01:17:17,000 --> 01:17:21,000
They clubbed us as we were trying to go downtown.

825
01:17:21,000 --> 01:17:30,000
And at one point, this young man's, at young point, this young woman was run over by one of the horses.

826
01:17:30,000 --> 01:17:34,000
So there was a guy near me who picked up a brick.

827
01:17:34,000 --> 01:17:37,000
I found out later that was his sister.

828
01:17:37,000 --> 01:17:52,000
I just, his sister, in terms of being a fellow black person for his real biological sister, he had a brick.

829
01:17:52,000 --> 01:17:54,000
And so I jumped on his back.

830
01:17:54,000 --> 01:17:56,000
I told him, you can't do that.

831
01:17:56,000 --> 01:17:57,000
You're going to be killed.

832
01:17:57,000 --> 01:17:58,000
We're going to be killed.

833
01:17:58,000 --> 01:18:02,000
If you throw that brick, he ran with me for about a block.

834
01:18:02,000 --> 01:18:05,000
This guy was about a line back of size.

835
01:18:05,000 --> 01:18:07,000
And I was about 140 pounds.

836
01:18:07,000 --> 01:18:10,000
But I'm talking to him all the time.

837
01:18:10,000 --> 01:18:14,000
And he put the brick down, came to his senses, turned around.

838
01:18:14,000 --> 01:18:17,000
The young lady got up and she was unhurt.

839
01:18:17,000 --> 01:18:25,000
So I wrote a rap about that as a matter of fact that my singing group used in some of our concerts.

840
01:18:25,000 --> 01:18:31,000
So that's the way I commemorated what happened at that particular time.

841
01:18:31,000 --> 01:18:34,000
I told her, I said, I jumped on his back.

842
01:18:34,000 --> 01:18:36,000
I said, brother, don't do that.

843
01:18:36,000 --> 01:18:37,000
They got too many guns.

844
01:18:37,000 --> 01:18:39,000
And that's a real fact.

845
01:18:39,000 --> 01:18:42,000
As he turned and looked around?

846
01:18:42,000 --> 01:18:46,000
Well, I don't remember all of it right now, but anyway.

847
01:18:46,000 --> 01:18:49,000
So we went back and licked our wounds.

848
01:18:49,000 --> 01:18:52,000
But then the third day, we marched down again.

849
01:18:52,000 --> 01:18:57,000
And by this time, we were five or six hundred people and they just couldn't stop us.

850
01:18:57,000 --> 01:19:02,000
So they decided they weren't going to bother us anymore.

851
01:19:02,000 --> 01:19:06,000
Until we got downtown and all along, we were picking up people.

852
01:19:06,000 --> 01:19:07,000
Picking up people.

853
01:19:07,000 --> 01:19:08,000
Picking up people.

854
01:19:08,000 --> 01:19:14,000
Until we got downtown to the state house where they had the Confederate flag and American flag.

855
01:19:14,000 --> 01:19:23,000
And the cops wouldn't let us, the city cops didn't let us march on the sidewalk.

856
01:19:23,000 --> 01:19:26,000
We couldn't stay cops so we couldn't march in the street.

857
01:19:26,000 --> 01:19:27,000
So we saw what the game was.

858
01:19:27,000 --> 01:19:29,000
We just sat down and they arrested us.

859
01:19:29,000 --> 01:19:31,000
There were too many people for the jail.

860
01:19:31,000 --> 01:19:35,000
So they put many of us in Kilby Prison Prison.

861
01:19:35,000 --> 01:19:39,000
And that's where we stayed for about a week.

862
01:19:39,000 --> 01:19:41,000
Do you remember the experience in prison?

863
01:19:41,000 --> 01:19:42,000
Yeah.

864
01:19:42,000 --> 01:19:45,000
Yeah.

865
01:19:45,000 --> 01:19:48,000
Worked long.

866
01:19:48,000 --> 01:19:50,000
Another.

867
01:19:50,000 --> 01:19:51,000
Famous.

868
01:19:51,000 --> 01:19:52,000
Not so famous.

869
01:19:52,000 --> 01:19:55,000
Outside of SNCC, but in SNCC.

870
01:19:55,000 --> 01:19:58,000
Very famous.

871
01:19:58,000 --> 01:20:03,000
We were in this big bullpen, 75 men.

872
01:20:03,000 --> 01:20:08,000
And about an equal amount of women on the other side.

873
01:20:08,000 --> 01:20:17,000
And so they just had mattresses with no blankets and it was cold.

874
01:20:17,000 --> 01:20:22,000
And that particular time in March in Alabama.

875
01:20:22,000 --> 01:20:25,000
So they just threw in a handful of dusty blankets.

876
01:20:25,000 --> 01:20:33,000
And of course, the bigger guys went for them and they were just taking their blankets.

877
01:20:33,000 --> 01:20:37,000
I'm standing on the side because that said I'm 40, 140 pounds.

878
01:20:37,000 --> 01:20:41,000
I wasn't about to get into that frill, that fray.

879
01:20:41,000 --> 01:20:45,000
So, worth long stood up on the table.

880
01:20:45,000 --> 01:20:50,000
Worth long is about five feet, six, five feet, seven, I guess.

881
01:20:50,000 --> 01:20:52,000
Eight, five feet, eight.

882
01:20:52,000 --> 01:20:54,000
But not a big guy.

883
01:20:54,000 --> 01:20:55,000
And he got on glasses.

884
01:20:55,000 --> 01:21:01,000
He looks like an organizer in the whole European context.

885
01:21:01,000 --> 01:21:05,000
And he says, hey, hey.

886
01:21:05,000 --> 01:21:07,000
Hey, he had to haul a few times.

887
01:21:07,000 --> 01:21:14,000
Said, I don't know about you, but if I was a man, I wouldn't take a blanket unless everybody had a blanket.

888
01:21:15,000 --> 01:21:17,000
And it's still fighting.

889
01:21:17,000 --> 01:21:21,000
I wouldn't take a blanket unless everybody got a blanket.

890
01:21:21,000 --> 01:21:26,000
So by this time, people were looking around at themselves.

891
01:21:26,000 --> 01:21:29,000
And one by one, those guys just came.

892
01:21:29,000 --> 01:21:30,000
Pow!

893
01:21:30,000 --> 01:21:33,000
Do those blankets there.

894
01:21:33,000 --> 01:21:36,000
Another moving moment in my life.

895
01:21:36,000 --> 01:21:43,000
Because from that point forward, we were organized.

896
01:21:43,000 --> 01:21:50,000
And the cops outside the jailers said, well, we don't have no more blankets.

897
01:21:50,000 --> 01:21:53,000
Well, we're told that we'll all be cold.

898
01:21:53,000 --> 01:21:56,000
And everybody said, yeah, that's right.

899
01:21:56,000 --> 01:22:00,000
So miraculously, they went and found some more blankets.

900
01:22:01,000 --> 01:22:03,000
And brought it in.

901
01:22:03,000 --> 01:22:08,000
And immediately we saw the value of organization.

902
01:22:08,000 --> 01:22:12,000
That's the first time I had ever seen it so quickly.

903
01:22:12,000 --> 01:22:17,000
It's one thing to thank good of yourself, because you did do what they expected you to do.

904
01:22:17,000 --> 01:22:21,000
It's another thing to actually see some material results.

905
01:22:21,000 --> 01:22:23,000
So that was a low hanging fruit.

906
01:22:23,000 --> 01:22:28,000
Now, eventually, worth got taken from us and put in solitary confinement,

907
01:22:28,000 --> 01:22:32,000
trying to integrate the church service or something.

908
01:22:32,000 --> 01:22:36,000
And so that left us leaderless.

909
01:22:36,000 --> 01:22:40,000
So me and a guy named Stu House became the leaders.

910
01:22:40,000 --> 01:22:46,000
Stu House was a young man from Detroit in SNCC.

911
01:22:46,000 --> 01:22:48,000
But he was in SNCC full time.

912
01:22:48,000 --> 01:22:50,000
This was my first time.

913
01:22:50,000 --> 01:22:52,000
So people listened to me.

914
01:22:52,000 --> 01:22:55,000
And I was very happy with that.

915
01:22:55,000 --> 01:22:58,000
Because we weren't talking about college folks now.

916
01:22:58,000 --> 01:23:01,000
We were talking about folks who were in college, some of us,

917
01:23:01,000 --> 01:23:04,000
but some of us who were not who speak brothers.

918
01:23:04,000 --> 01:23:08,000
So I was able to learn that folks listening to what I had to say.

919
01:23:08,000 --> 01:23:11,000
That was my first leadership role in the movement

920
01:23:11,000 --> 01:23:15,000
was to hold that cell together for those seven days along with Stu.

921
01:23:15,000 --> 01:23:18,000
What were some of the other issues you had to deal with in the summer?

922
01:23:18,000 --> 01:23:20,000
People wanted to get out.

923
01:23:20,000 --> 01:23:24,000
People who got swept up in and that the spirit of moment and wanted to leave.

924
01:23:24,000 --> 01:23:26,000
We had to keep up the morale.

925
01:23:26,000 --> 01:23:27,000
We sang.

926
01:23:27,000 --> 01:23:28,000
We talked.

927
01:23:28,000 --> 01:23:29,000
We sang.

928
01:23:29,000 --> 01:23:30,000
We talked.

929
01:23:30,000 --> 01:23:34,000
We refereed fights over food.

930
01:23:34,000 --> 01:23:36,000
One guy went, we wanted to keep his food.

931
01:23:36,000 --> 01:23:39,000
He didn't want to eat it all at one time.

932
01:23:39,000 --> 01:23:41,000
So he'd hidden it under the mattress.

933
01:23:41,000 --> 01:23:44,000
And somebody else saw it over there and just went over there and took it.

934
01:23:44,000 --> 01:23:45,000
He wanted to fight.

935
01:23:45,000 --> 01:23:47,000
So we had to stop that.

936
01:23:47,000 --> 01:23:48,000
Comed it on.

937
01:23:48,000 --> 01:23:51,000
The freedom song was very helpful.

938
01:23:51,000 --> 01:23:54,000
We made a pact that we were going to all get out together.

939
01:23:54,000 --> 01:23:59,000
But because I came from Massachusetts and because we were good at what we did.

940
01:23:59,000 --> 01:24:02,000
Remember I told you we raised money for people who were in jail.

941
01:24:02,000 --> 01:24:09,000
Well then it came back to me because we very quickly in Massachusetts raised money to get me out of jail.

942
01:24:09,000 --> 01:24:11,000
So I didn't want to go.

943
01:24:11,000 --> 01:24:14,000
So the lawyers told me if you don't use this money,

944
01:24:14,000 --> 01:24:17,000
somebody else is going to use it and we don't know when you're going to get out.

945
01:24:17,000 --> 01:24:19,000
We got to take you when you come.

946
01:24:19,000 --> 01:24:21,000
We got to get a money attached to a person.

947
01:24:21,000 --> 01:24:22,000
We're going to bail people out.

948
01:24:22,000 --> 01:24:24,000
It's not going to be all of nothing.

949
01:24:24,000 --> 01:24:25,000
So reluctantly I left.

950
01:24:25,000 --> 01:24:28,000
Me and a few others at that time.

951
01:24:28,000 --> 01:24:30,000
Say goodbye.

952
01:24:30,000 --> 01:24:36,000
And by that time the march had reached town.

953
01:24:36,000 --> 01:24:42,000
So we went out to the big cornfield or fairground or whatever that place was.

954
01:24:42,000 --> 01:24:47,000
Where they had the final massing before going into town the next morning.

955
01:24:47,000 --> 01:24:49,000
And that's where you had all the stars.

956
01:24:49,000 --> 01:24:53,000
Harry Belafonte, Nina Simone.

957
01:24:53,000 --> 01:24:55,000
Who else was there?

958
01:24:55,000 --> 01:24:57,000
Who else was there?

959
01:24:57,000 --> 01:24:58,000
I saw.

960
01:24:58,000 --> 01:25:02,000
Because I was me and a few other people who had been bailed out by that time.

961
01:25:02,000 --> 01:25:08,000
We were known as the ones who were just released from Kilby State Prison.

962
01:25:08,000 --> 01:25:10,000
That was our title.

963
01:25:10,000 --> 01:25:14,000
So it was like the waters were part of it.

964
01:25:14,000 --> 01:25:16,000
We were most welcome.

965
01:25:16,000 --> 01:25:17,000
It was a rainy day.

966
01:25:17,000 --> 01:25:18,000
I remember that.

967
01:25:18,000 --> 01:25:22,000
Well, I didn't care about that because I was sad about those guys who were still there.

968
01:25:22,000 --> 01:25:30,000
Because I had said I wouldn't go and leave but a circumstances wouldn't allow me to stay.

969
01:25:30,000 --> 01:25:31,000
So we helped.

970
01:25:31,000 --> 01:25:37,000
We did what we could to make the thing to accommodate what was going on.

971
01:25:37,000 --> 01:25:40,000
The person in charge at that point was another guy.

972
01:25:40,000 --> 01:25:44,000
I was very impressed with Ivanhoe Donaldson.

973
01:25:44,000 --> 01:25:49,000
He was one of the few people I found out later who agreed to work with SCLC

974
01:25:49,000 --> 01:25:54,000
from the SNCC side to make this thing happen along with John Lewis.

975
01:25:54,000 --> 01:25:56,000
He was his own man.

976
01:25:56,000 --> 01:25:58,000
He decided I didn't want to do that.

977
01:25:58,000 --> 01:26:02,000
So he was doing logistics as he often did and did it very well.

978
01:26:02,000 --> 01:26:09,000
So my impression of him was a very calm but focused young man

979
01:26:09,000 --> 01:26:13,000
with a walkie talkie wearing a yellow rain slicker.

980
01:26:13,000 --> 01:26:15,000
That was Ivan Holdon.

981
01:26:15,000 --> 01:26:18,000
I wanted to be just like him when I grew up.

982
01:26:18,000 --> 01:26:23,000
Although he was the deathwitch older than me, that was my idol for a long time.

983
01:26:23,000 --> 01:26:29,000
Because I saw him take charge kind of guy in a very hostile situation.

984
01:26:29,000 --> 01:26:31,000
And that's what he did very well.

985
01:26:31,000 --> 01:26:38,000
So my last memory of that was people were marching in and I really was tired

986
01:26:38,000 --> 01:26:41,000
physically and mentally.

987
01:26:41,000 --> 01:26:45,000
So there was a first aid Jeep.

988
01:26:45,000 --> 01:26:54,000
There was the last vehicle, the very last vehicle, the very last set of people in the march.

989
01:26:54,000 --> 01:26:56,000
I got in that Jeep.

990
01:26:56,000 --> 01:27:01,000
I was the last person because I could look out and see the road which we came.

991
01:27:01,000 --> 01:27:04,000
But at that point was the void of anybody.

992
01:27:04,000 --> 01:27:08,000
Because all the police by that time had cleared away the races.

993
01:27:08,000 --> 01:27:13,000
But there was my thought that somebody would come up and shoot us from the back.

994
01:27:13,000 --> 01:27:16,000
And if that had been done, I'd have been the one they had shot.

995
01:27:16,000 --> 01:27:18,000
But it didn't happen fortunately.

996
01:27:18,000 --> 01:27:23,000
Later on going back, Viola Liuzzo got shot.

997
01:27:23,000 --> 01:27:28,000
She was the person who was shot last, I think, in this demonstration.

998
01:27:28,000 --> 01:27:33,000
Taking people back along the highway to Selma.

999
01:27:33,000 --> 01:27:35,000
Let me take the phone.

1000
01:27:35,000 --> 01:27:38,000
So, these are the other reference shoes of work long.

1001
01:27:38,000 --> 01:27:43,000
Did you know that you're in good shape in California and in the Pacific?

1002
01:27:43,000 --> 01:27:44,000
I talked to work.

1003
01:27:44,000 --> 01:27:46,000
Work was sick.

1004
01:27:46,000 --> 01:27:48,000
He couldn't come to the 50th anniversary.

1005
01:27:48,000 --> 01:27:49,000
So I talked to him on the phone.

1006
01:27:49,000 --> 01:27:51,000
He's in Atlanta.

1007
01:27:51,000 --> 01:27:54,000
Now, he did some music.

1008
01:27:54,000 --> 01:27:56,000
He did some ethno music colleges.

1009
01:27:56,000 --> 01:27:59,000
He was an ethno music colleges.

1010
01:27:59,000 --> 01:28:01,000
I don't know officially on that.

1011
01:28:01,000 --> 01:28:06,000
He went out and found old blues singers and hooked them up.

1012
01:28:06,000 --> 01:28:09,000
I made a movie about blues together.

1013
01:28:09,000 --> 01:28:10,000
Is that right?

1014
01:28:10,000 --> 01:28:11,000
That's how you know him, huh?

1015
01:28:11,000 --> 01:28:12,000
Yeah.

1016
01:28:12,000 --> 01:28:14,000
And I know he's known in legend and song.

1017
01:28:14,000 --> 01:28:16,000
But you know, not very many people have stories about him.

1018
01:28:16,000 --> 01:28:17,000
Yeah.

1019
01:28:17,000 --> 01:28:18,000
Well, there you got one.

1020
01:28:18,000 --> 01:28:19,000
He was a good one.

1021
01:28:19,000 --> 01:28:20,000
He was my man.

1022
01:28:20,000 --> 01:28:21,000
That was my other.

1023
01:28:21,000 --> 01:28:23,000
I wanted to be just like, worse.

1024
01:28:23,000 --> 01:28:26,000
Because he calmed the waters.

1025
01:28:26,000 --> 01:28:28,000
Let's take a picture.

1026
01:28:28,000 --> 01:28:29,000
Okay.

1027
01:28:29,000 --> 01:28:31,000
We're back on after short break.

1028
01:28:31,000 --> 01:28:34,000
You were recalling another person you met in?

1029
01:28:34,000 --> 01:28:35,000
Posey.

1030
01:28:35,000 --> 01:28:36,000
Yeah.

1031
01:28:36,000 --> 01:28:37,000
Posey Lombard.

1032
01:28:37,000 --> 01:28:40,000
No, I knew Posey from Smith.

1033
01:28:40,000 --> 01:28:45,000
Posey was a young white woman from Massachusetts, who was now dead because of a car accident.

1034
01:28:45,000 --> 01:28:48,000
Great artist, visual artist.

1035
01:28:48,000 --> 01:28:54,000
But she committed to work for the movement after that and went to work somewhere in Georgia.

1036
01:28:54,000 --> 01:28:55,000
I believe it's unique.

1037
01:28:55,000 --> 01:28:58,000
But she and worth were close.

1038
01:28:58,000 --> 01:29:04,000
And that's about all I know about worth from there.

1039
01:29:04,000 --> 01:29:11,000
I mean, I've only talked to him that one time since then, and I was hoping he was going to come, but they told me he was sick.

1040
01:29:11,000 --> 01:29:13,000
So I called him talk to him.

1041
01:29:13,000 --> 01:29:15,000
And he seemed upbeat.

1042
01:29:15,000 --> 01:29:19,000
But clearly, he was not the worth long that I knew.

1043
01:29:19,000 --> 01:29:21,000
He lost a step.

1044
01:29:22,000 --> 01:29:37,000
Do you think back to the moment when you and Stu have such shows and the kind of leader of the 75 folks in the recording room?

1045
01:29:37,000 --> 01:29:38,000
Nobody told us.

1046
01:29:38,000 --> 01:29:39,000
We just evolved.

1047
01:29:39,000 --> 01:29:40,000
That's what I wanted to ask.

1048
01:29:40,000 --> 01:29:42,000
How do you think that?

1049
01:29:42,000 --> 01:29:50,000
What's it about you that made you ready and attracted to the day for that leadership role in that context?

1050
01:29:50,000 --> 01:29:52,000
That's a good question.

1051
01:29:52,000 --> 01:29:58,000
I saw things were going wrong and I spoke up and people listened to me.

1052
01:29:58,000 --> 01:30:00,000
And the same thing with Stu.

1053
01:30:00,000 --> 01:30:02,000
Stu had a little more experience.

1054
01:30:02,000 --> 01:30:06,000
I had had the experience of running a civil rights group at a college.

1055
01:30:06,000 --> 01:30:10,000
He at least had had the experience of being with SNCC somewhere.

1056
01:30:10,000 --> 01:30:14,000
So I had no experience in dealing with folks other than college types.

1057
01:30:15,000 --> 01:30:19,000
But I just decided that it was something that had to be done.

1058
01:30:19,000 --> 01:30:21,000
So I just stepped up.

1059
01:30:21,000 --> 01:30:27,000
How long did you and Alabama before going back up to Canada?

1060
01:30:27,000 --> 01:30:28,000
Oh, right after that.

1061
01:30:28,000 --> 01:30:32,000
We got back in our cars and we started going back.

1062
01:30:32,000 --> 01:30:36,000
I guess it was the same day that the march was over.

1063
01:30:36,000 --> 01:30:38,000
That night, we were headed north.

1064
01:30:38,000 --> 01:30:44,000
Any further thoughts about the combination of the march?

1065
01:30:44,000 --> 01:30:45,000
Yeah.

1066
01:30:45,000 --> 01:30:53,000
Posey was driving my father's station wagon when I heard on the radio that Viola, Lee, Utah was killed.

1067
01:30:53,000 --> 01:30:56,000
Just kicked me in my stomach.

1068
01:30:56,000 --> 01:30:58,000
Everybody there.

1069
01:30:58,000 --> 01:31:00,000
We had a moment.

1070
01:31:00,000 --> 01:31:04,000
And there was a screwdriver in my father's car.

1071
01:31:04,000 --> 01:31:06,000
And I just picked it up.

1072
01:31:06,000 --> 01:31:11,000
And I said, if they come for me, this is not going to be a nonviolent confrontation.

1073
01:31:17,000 --> 01:31:24,000
After you return, you were a graduation was just in front of you a few months ahead of you.

1074
01:31:24,000 --> 01:31:32,000
And you would make a choice to go to Newark NJ because of the connection to Tom Aydin.

1075
01:31:32,000 --> 01:31:39,000
So let's turn the conversation towards all these many years that you've been in Newark NJ.

1076
01:31:39,000 --> 01:31:43,000
In the early summer of 65, you can't hear.

1077
01:31:43,000 --> 01:31:50,000
Tom Hayden was back in the Connecticut Valley, as we called it, for some reason.

1078
01:31:50,000 --> 01:31:55,000
He'd been there in March for the Civil Rights Conference, but he was back to Amherst doing something.

1079
01:31:55,000 --> 01:31:57,000
So he sought me out.

1080
01:31:57,000 --> 01:32:01,000
And he wanted me to come work in Newark NJ because of my work that he knew with the conference.

1081
01:32:01,000 --> 01:32:05,000
And he also knew I had gone down to Alabama.

1082
01:32:05,000 --> 01:32:09,000
So it was like my only interview for a job.

1083
01:32:09,000 --> 01:32:11,000
No one got it else wanted to interview me.

1084
01:32:11,000 --> 01:32:14,000
And I didn't want to be interviewed.

1085
01:32:14,000 --> 01:32:19,000
I don't even know if I had found out I was accepted at law school at that point.

1086
01:32:19,000 --> 01:32:21,000
I don't think I had.

1087
01:32:21,000 --> 01:32:28,000
So he said the Civil Rights Movement is over.

1088
01:32:29,000 --> 01:32:31,000
And I said, what do you mean?

1089
01:32:31,000 --> 01:32:34,000
He said, Selman among them, that was it.

1090
01:32:34,000 --> 01:32:36,000
You got to vote a rights law.

1091
01:32:36,000 --> 01:32:39,000
There's just not going to be anything else.

1092
01:32:39,000 --> 01:32:40,000
And Tom was like that.

1093
01:32:40,000 --> 01:32:48,000
He had kind of a pression view about a lot of things.

1094
01:32:48,000 --> 01:32:52,000
So he was telling me something that he'd figured out before other people had.

1095
01:32:52,000 --> 01:32:54,000
So I thought about it too.

1096
01:32:55,000 --> 01:33:00,000
And maybe within a day or so I got to let I say I was going to go to law school.

1097
01:33:00,000 --> 01:33:03,000
And so I said I could kill two birds with one stone.

1098
01:33:03,000 --> 01:33:08,000
I can go to Newark NJ and still go to law school that summer.

1099
01:33:08,000 --> 01:33:12,000
I'm sorry, after that summer, if I didn't like Newark NJ, I would just go on my way.

1100
01:33:12,000 --> 01:33:15,000
But if I did, I would call that my home.

1101
01:33:15,000 --> 01:33:18,000
And the law degree would be applied there.

1102
01:33:18,000 --> 01:33:21,000
So as it worked out, I did like Newark NJ.

1103
01:33:21,000 --> 01:33:25,000
And I said, I have a lot of adventures there, which you probably want me to tell you about.

1104
01:33:25,000 --> 01:33:27,000
But that's how I came to go there.

1105
01:33:27,000 --> 01:33:32,000
I went home at the end of the semester, graduated.

1106
01:33:32,000 --> 01:33:35,000
My parents wanted to be formal graduation.

1107
01:33:35,000 --> 01:33:38,000
Of course, I didn't particularly care.

1108
01:33:38,000 --> 01:33:45,000
So I went for the essay and went home and came back up on a bus to Newark NJ.

1109
01:33:45,000 --> 01:33:56,000
Did you just mention that Hayden already was looking past all the work in the south to a new type of phase of the movement.

1110
01:33:56,000 --> 01:34:05,000
And I know that in many respects, Newark NJ then would be a place where the movement came and found in other contexts.

1111
01:34:05,000 --> 01:34:07,000
Newark NJ came in North.

1112
01:34:07,000 --> 01:34:12,000
Did you explicitly understand that that was your project, or you came in North?

1113
01:34:12,000 --> 01:34:15,000
Well, I did.

1114
01:34:15,000 --> 01:34:18,000
The movement had already come North.

1115
01:34:18,000 --> 01:34:22,000
I just didn't think about it as being the movement.

1116
01:34:22,000 --> 01:34:29,000
Because what I was doing in Harlem, trying to build a playground with Julian T. Houston in 1964.

1117
01:34:29,000 --> 01:34:30,000
That was part of the movement.

1118
01:34:30,000 --> 01:34:33,000
The Northern Student Movement was part of the movement.

1119
01:34:33,000 --> 01:34:37,000
I just didn't see me as part of that until Tom brought it home.

1120
01:34:37,000 --> 01:34:40,000
So SDS had already been formed to do the same thing.

1121
01:34:40,000 --> 01:34:45,000
I mean, the ERAP projects were all in the North based on that same concept.

1122
01:34:45,000 --> 01:34:50,000
We have to take on what's going on in the North because it's harder.

1123
01:34:50,000 --> 01:34:54,000
It's more about class and their minds than race.

1124
01:34:54,000 --> 01:34:57,000
They were to be proved wrong.

1125
01:34:57,000 --> 01:35:01,000
But that was the foundation that brought them here.

1126
01:35:01,000 --> 01:35:08,000
These young people in the students for Democratic society or SDS, they were not Marxists, but they understood Marx.

1127
01:35:08,000 --> 01:35:14,000
They understood Marxism, just as Julian T. Houston and Pigeon had.

1128
01:35:14,000 --> 01:35:23,000
And when you applied the class analysis, they thought that racism could be overcome

1129
01:35:23,000 --> 01:35:33,000
if we adjusted the class background to include more people in the economy of this country.

1130
01:35:33,000 --> 01:35:39,000
So they came to New York based on getting people to get jobs.

1131
01:35:39,000 --> 01:35:45,000
When they came here, they were supposed to be working with a group called the Clinton Hill Neighborhood Corporation,

1132
01:35:45,000 --> 01:35:51,000
which was an older group of white liberals, mostly Jewish,

1133
01:35:51,000 --> 01:35:58,000
who had been in Clinton Hill, which is to the south of here, for many years, since the 1950s.

1134
01:35:58,000 --> 01:36:05,000
Fighting progressive cause, fighting the urban renewal, trying to make sure that there was no discrimination against blacks.

1135
01:36:05,000 --> 01:36:14,000
And they were an integrated group of mostly white Jewish homeowners with some black homeowners as well.

1136
01:36:14,000 --> 01:36:20,000
And some working, they all had a working class basis of one kind or another, but they were professionals in it as well.

1137
01:36:20,000 --> 01:36:26,000
So it was an interesting mix of people. But to make a long story short,

1138
01:36:26,000 --> 01:36:33,000
the SDS people thought they were working with poor people, and they weren't.

1139
01:36:33,000 --> 01:36:39,000
And the Clinton Hill folks thought the SDS people were going to just pick up from where they were,

1140
01:36:39,000 --> 01:36:42,000
and they didn't want to do that, so they were the split.

1141
01:36:42,000 --> 01:36:49,000
So by the time I got here, Tom Hayden and the other SDS people had moved down the hill into lower Clinton Hill,

1142
01:36:49,000 --> 01:37:00,000
where there were fewer homeowners, practically no homeowners with some, and a lot of tenants and mostly black,

1143
01:37:00,000 --> 01:37:06,000
mostly black working class and poor living in the same neighborhood.

1144
01:37:06,000 --> 01:37:09,000
So they had to already organize people when I got here.

1145
01:37:09,000 --> 01:37:16,000
They had been here a year and they had a base of several hundred people, maybe 200 people,

1146
01:37:16,000 --> 01:37:21,000
and several on several blocks.

1147
01:37:21,000 --> 01:37:29,000
And the issue that they came, which was unemployment, that didn't work.

1148
01:37:29,000 --> 01:37:33,000
People didn't want to talk about the employment status. And as Betty Maul has explained to me,

1149
01:37:33,000 --> 01:37:37,000
one of the black folks who I met while I was here,

1150
01:37:37,000 --> 01:37:41,000
the people had jobs, they were just bad jobs, they were underpaying jobs.

1151
01:37:41,000 --> 01:37:47,000
It was not that there was a lot of unemployment like it is now, but it was under employment.

1152
01:37:47,000 --> 01:37:51,000
It was the beginning of the era of the working poor.

1153
01:37:51,000 --> 01:37:54,000
We didn't know it at that time, but that's really what it was.

1154
01:37:54,000 --> 01:38:03,000
But what was wrong with people's mind was police brutality and landlords and stormers gouging people.

1155
01:38:03,000 --> 01:38:08,000
Because you didn't have credit cards then, people got credit and people,

1156
01:38:08,000 --> 01:38:15,000
the stormers were up to credit and then there was a whole lot of baits and switch in terms of the product that you got.

1157
01:38:15,000 --> 01:38:21,000
So that's what the end cup was doing, taking on those kinds of issues.

1158
01:38:21,000 --> 01:38:26,000
And how did you fund your way into a role here?

1159
01:38:26,000 --> 01:38:29,000
What commanded your attention?

1160
01:38:29,000 --> 01:38:34,000
What captivated you?

1161
01:38:34,000 --> 01:38:37,000
You and all this work?

1162
01:38:37,000 --> 01:38:41,000
You mean once I was here, I wanted to be an organizer.

1163
01:38:41,000 --> 01:38:45,000
I saw that as really what I could get from being here.

1164
01:38:45,000 --> 01:38:51,000
The SNCC experience taught me how to walk through the valley of the shadow of death

1165
01:38:51,000 --> 01:38:55,000
and the people who were here, but I wanted to be an organizer.

1166
01:38:55,000 --> 01:38:59,000
And here we were on a frontier that SNCC could really not compete with.

1167
01:38:59,000 --> 01:39:01,000
Because you did have that class aspect.

1168
01:39:01,000 --> 01:39:07,000
I understood class by this point because I had been talking about it and reading about it and studying it.

1169
01:39:07,000 --> 01:39:10,000
So I was ready for that challenge.

1170
01:39:10,000 --> 01:39:15,000
How do you get black people organized in a context that's not purely racial.

1171
01:39:15,000 --> 01:39:17,000
Not purely racialized.

1172
01:39:17,000 --> 01:39:26,000
But where you're not going to have people with white masks who are terrorists per se,

1173
01:39:26,000 --> 01:39:29,000
but you have the police who are doing it legally.

1174
01:39:29,000 --> 01:39:33,000
Where you're not going to have people who get thrown off of plantation,

1175
01:39:33,000 --> 01:39:40,000
but people who didn't have enough money to make their way based upon a little job that they did have.

1176
01:39:40,000 --> 01:39:47,000
Where you don't have folks that say, well, you can't live here because the whole area was black,

1177
01:39:47,000 --> 01:39:54,000
but the housing was so bad, in some cases, you wouldn't want to keep your dog there.

1178
01:39:54,000 --> 01:39:56,000
So how do you fight that? How do you get people involved?

1179
01:39:56,000 --> 01:39:57,000
That's what kept me here.

1180
01:39:57,000 --> 01:40:01,000
And I wanted to organize people to fight that kind of fight.

1181
01:40:01,000 --> 01:40:05,000
You mentioned the Newark Community Union Project, the New York Community Unity Project.

1182
01:40:05,000 --> 01:40:11,000
The Newark Community Union Project, the Newark Community Union Project, the Newark Community Union Project.

1183
01:40:11,000 --> 01:40:19,000
And it's set about this program and you also would work with Bill Hagen.

1184
01:40:19,000 --> 01:40:31,000
Can you describe the range of organizations trying to begin this effort in New York to find some progressive changes in the industry?

1185
01:40:31,000 --> 01:40:36,000
Yeah, that's a good question because Newark Community Union Project was not the first by enemies.

1186
01:40:36,000 --> 01:40:45,000
There were people here who were already struggling against that same array of new enemy, if you will, not new per se,

1187
01:40:45,000 --> 01:40:51,000
but that newly discovered array of forces that were keeping people down.

1188
01:40:51,000 --> 01:40:56,000
So, COAR was one of the allies of New York.

1189
01:40:56,000 --> 01:41:01,000
And there were various combinations of people associated with CORE

1190
01:41:01,000 --> 01:41:04,000
and various other organizations, the names of which I forget.

1191
01:41:04,000 --> 01:41:08,000
One was called Anville, ANVIL, I remember that.

1192
01:41:08,000 --> 01:41:18,000
And there were some black labor unions and some preachers who managed to stay out of the clutches of the then mayor, Hugh Addonizio.

1193
01:41:18,000 --> 01:41:20,000
So that was the coalition.

1194
01:41:20,000 --> 01:41:36,000
There were some white rabbis, rabbi dressers, and dragged through the mud and a CORE demonstration protesting lack of construction jobs at a school that was being constructed here at the barrenger high school demonstration.

1195
01:41:36,000 --> 01:41:46,000
So, you had a black and white coalition that was liberal, I would call it liberal, mostly liberal.

1196
01:41:46,000 --> 01:41:50,000
And the Newark Community Union Project students came on, they were the radicals.

1197
01:41:50,000 --> 01:41:59,000
Because they were insisted upon a form of democracy that nobody was willing to allow.

1198
01:41:59,000 --> 01:42:04,000
And it was a form of democracy that had not taken root in this town.

1199
01:42:04,000 --> 01:42:06,000
But the Newark Community Union Project people said, let the people decide.

1200
01:42:06,000 --> 01:42:15,000
And the people were then meeting to all hours of the night, just like in SNCC, people met all hours of the night to make most of the basic decisions.

1201
01:42:15,000 --> 01:42:19,000
It wasn't in the bureaucracy, it wasn't in to one leader.

1202
01:42:19,000 --> 01:42:25,000
Although, as it turned out, the leader was Tom.

1203
01:42:25,000 --> 01:42:30,000
I mean, Tom was the main man. He was the big man on campus, so to speak.

1204
01:42:30,000 --> 01:42:37,000
And then there was Barry Kellace. He was the big man also vying for competing for that same position.

1205
01:42:37,000 --> 01:42:41,000
Although they wouldn't have said it, but looking at it from the outside.

1206
01:42:41,000 --> 01:42:47,000
There were the community people who had their own set of standards for what they wanted to be done.

1207
01:42:47,000 --> 01:42:55,000
And there were people like Terry Jefferson, who you didn't really do anything unless Terry said what had to be done.

1208
01:42:55,000 --> 01:42:57,000
She was the office manager.

1209
01:42:57,000 --> 01:43:04,000
You had Bessie Smith, who was found and discovered by the Newark Community Union Project people.

1210
01:43:04,000 --> 01:43:10,000
And she and her husband, Thurmond Smith, were like mainstays at the organization.

1211
01:43:10,000 --> 01:43:22,000
That's how we got all got together and fought Badland Lords, Bratton Roaches, little police brutality.

1212
01:43:22,000 --> 01:43:34,000
I see that was interesting. The police brutality situation, and this is more from my review of the written record about Newark Community Union Project as written by some of the organizers.

1213
01:43:34,000 --> 01:43:41,000
A lot of the organizers felt not a lot of them, but some of the organizers felt the police brutality was too volatile.

1214
01:43:41,000 --> 01:43:49,000
Why? Because it was racial. There were white cops beating black heads.

1215
01:43:49,000 --> 01:43:51,000
And you couldn't get away from that.

1216
01:43:51,000 --> 01:44:00,000
And this was something they really didn't want to deal with because they couldn't control the emotion of the people who were affected.

1217
01:44:00,000 --> 01:44:03,000
And they thought it was only to arrive. So they said let's core deal with that.

1218
01:44:03,000 --> 01:44:13,000
So core had weakly demonstrations against police brutality because at that time people were getting beat up regularly and some people being killed.

1219
01:44:13,000 --> 01:44:28,000
As a matter of fact, I came to New York the first day I came. I was in a demonstration, a core demonstration against police brutality because of a black man that was shot by a cop named Hank Martinez.

1220
01:44:29,000 --> 01:44:36,000
Now I didn't know Henry "Hank" Martinez at that time. I didn't even associate him with anything other than the fact that he was a cop.

1221
01:44:36,000 --> 01:44:45,000
Years later, the same Henry "Hank" Martinez ran for City Council and won from the East Ward and he and I became friends.

1222
01:44:46,000 --> 01:44:58,000
I had no idea that was the same man that I was in my first demonstration against on my first day in New York, probably my first hour in New York.

1223
01:44:58,000 --> 01:45:03,000
I had no idea because it's completely different. I didn't see how that man could have shot somebody.

1224
01:45:03,000 --> 01:45:11,000
And I didn't, you know how I found out? I found out by doing some research about what was going on on that corner on that day.

1225
01:45:11,000 --> 01:45:16,000
And I haven't yet to talk to him about that. Probably won't.

1226
01:45:16,000 --> 01:45:29,000
How did you judge the course what will happen in the summer of 67 is that Newark Rebellion will suddenly dominate all of so much of how people think about this history of the city.

1227
01:45:29,000 --> 01:45:40,000
Prior to that point, all the spestering tension, police brutality, terrible conditions in housing, under employment and then how did you feel about your work?

1228
01:45:40,000 --> 01:45:52,000
Your progress so to speak against the, against the goal of starting something that we yield results. How did you feel across the first 24 months you were here?

1229
01:45:52,000 --> 01:45:58,000
Well, when I first came to New York, I wasn't here for 24 months straight. I was here for the summer.

1230
01:45:58,000 --> 01:46:04,000
And then you went to New York. Remember I went to New Haven to Yale. So you have to give me another yardstick.

1231
01:46:04,000 --> 01:46:16,000
And my first several weeks, I realized one thing that race was going to be a bigger issue than these kids were able to deal with.

1232
01:46:16,000 --> 01:46:26,000
So Phil and I were the two black college types on campus, so to speak. And we talked about it all the time.

1233
01:46:26,000 --> 01:46:40,000
And we were becoming more and more difficult for white people to go out and organize black people. Already, SNCC had said, I think in 1966, maybe not already, but there was a whole lot of conversation about that.

1234
01:46:40,000 --> 01:46:49,000
And the final act spell in 1966, Phil said, and SNCC said, white people, you got to go out and organize amongst white people.

1235
01:46:49,000 --> 01:46:58,000
And Carmichael replaces Lewis. And Carmichael replaces Lewis at a very tumultuous meeting where Lewis went away thinking he was the president.

1236
01:46:58,000 --> 01:47:06,000
And they reconvene the meeting and put Carmichael in. And that's when the whole process of the purge began.

1237
01:47:06,000 --> 01:47:08,000
You were there. That's that SNIC out there.

1238
01:47:08,000 --> 01:47:15,000
No, I wasn't there. No, no, no. I was not a part of the SNCC hierarchy. I was just a grunt in Montgomery. That's all I was.

1239
01:47:15,000 --> 01:47:30,000
A soldier in the Army in the Lord. So I heard about this later, but it didn't happen overnight because people were saying within SNCC and within Northern student movement and other places, white people can't do this.

1240
01:47:30,000 --> 01:47:41,000
Race is predominant. Malcolm X, there's a lot of what he says people didn't go along with, but a lot of it people did go along with.

1241
01:47:41,000 --> 01:47:49,000
And there were other nationalists raising that same issue. The integrationist in the movement were losing ground.

1242
01:47:49,000 --> 01:47:58,000
King was losing ground on that level because he saw it himself. I can't go out and tell him people to be non-violent in the face of the kind of violence I saw in Chicago.

1243
01:47:58,000 --> 01:48:06,000
And I can't keep continuing to tell the nationalists that they're wrong unless America gives me something to work with.

1244
01:48:06,000 --> 01:48:22,000
So that was militating against it. And we saw it on our little microcosm here in Newark NJ because of the police brutality demonstrations that just were just that far from getting out of hand because people had just taken as much as they could take and just weren't going to take it anymore.

1245
01:48:22,000 --> 01:48:36,000
So SNCC then felt organized SNCC in Newark NJ with the support of Tom at the second SDS office that we had in town which was in the Central Ward.

1246
01:48:36,000 --> 01:48:53,000
You had the South Ward which was based on the landlord tenant and the store problems. But in the Central Ward, the end cup office here was just kind of like a hangout for young men mostly.

1247
01:48:53,000 --> 01:49:01,000
And that's where Tom spent most of his time cultivating people here. And SNCC and Phil and eventually that became the SNIC office.

1248
01:49:01,000 --> 01:49:11,000
Whether it was in 65 or I don't think no, because 65 or I was still here maybe after I left in the summer it became the SNCC office as well as the end cup office.

1249
01:49:11,000 --> 01:49:21,000
But then Phil and SNCC began to take that separate line of black power.

1250
01:49:21,000 --> 01:49:35,000
So it was impossible to do anything in Newark NJ without addressing the racial issue.

1251
01:49:35,000 --> 01:49:44,000
And so we looked at the double ed sword that white organizers presented. Some people like to talk to white people.

1252
01:49:44,000 --> 01:49:53,000
They thought it was great that some white people wanted to come in and they would hood and help some people didn't.

1253
01:49:53,000 --> 01:50:05,000
Newark NJ at that time in 1965 was full of people who had just come from the South. This was part, this was the tail end of the second of the second great migration from the South.

1254
01:50:05,000 --> 01:50:15,000
So people were here who had the Southern experience. And a lot of people didn't trust white people. A lot of people love white people and wanted to be with the white people.

1255
01:50:15,000 --> 01:50:29,000
But that same racism that created that kind of of of of inkling within the want to be mentality also created a great deal of hostility.

1256
01:50:29,000 --> 01:50:39,000
And we were beginning to see the more that there was more hostility. And we couldn't get people to understand that these white people over here are different.

1257
01:50:39,000 --> 01:50:45,000
Took up too much time and then did you to explain that. And I found that on the block.

1258
01:50:45,000 --> 01:50:53,000
Because at some point I was organized I was giving my own block to work with Karenna. Karenna and I had a new block Karenna fails.

1259
01:50:53,000 --> 01:51:01,000
I must have been doing all right because they're signed me and Corinna to work with each other on breaking open new block over an essential ward.

1260
01:51:01,000 --> 01:51:06,000
The issue there was a stock light. How are we going to get a stock light? That's what the people said they wanted to do.

1261
01:51:06,000 --> 01:51:15,000
And amongst the people was a man named Billy. And Billy said I can work with you. But I can't work with her.

1262
01:51:15,000 --> 01:51:27,000
Later on Billy became a Muslim. All he already was. I'm not so sure which. But he knew the Muslim. He knew the end of the nation of Islam line.

1263
01:51:27,000 --> 01:51:37,000
And he challenged me. And it made me worry. Feeling I talked about it. I didn't want to stop working with the students. And I didn't.

1264
01:51:37,000 --> 01:51:50,000
But they rested at summer because I still believe in an integrated movement. And I thought the whole class issue was the best way to deal with it. But it was becoming more and more impossible.

1265
01:51:50,000 --> 01:52:06,000
You lived together. Yeah. Yeah. Was there any point at which you obviously, you know, FBI, Coentel, Pro, House of American Activities Committee?

1266
01:52:06,000 --> 01:52:21,000
Because you all be parts of the story open. Did you have any sense that you were already folks who were being kind of watched and monitored very closely?

1267
01:52:21,000 --> 01:52:45,000
I was a grunt. I was a grunt in Montgomery. I was a grunt up here in New York doing what they told me to do. Until I got my block. And I had some kind of say so what was supposed to happen there in conjunction with Karina.

1268
01:52:45,000 --> 01:53:14,000
A little later on, I guess it was in 1968. I look back at that point because in 1968 there was a HUAC Committee meeting. And at that point, some policeman came from New York and presented a letter from me to Tom Hayden saying, yes, I'm going to come to New York.

1269
01:53:14,000 --> 01:53:21,000
Now, I didn't give him that letter. I'm sure Tom didn't give him that letter. Who the hell gave him the letter?

1270
01:53:21,000 --> 01:53:34,000
Another and he accused me and it was really an accusation. He accused me of living with his hell-raiser, Phil Hutchings, who everybody knows as a hell-raiser because he's affiliated with SNCC.

1271
01:53:34,000 --> 01:53:47,000
And they were all trying to blame us for Newark Rebellion, for Newark Rebellion. That was the conspiracy. That was the context. That's how this HUAC convened took place.

1272
01:53:47,000 --> 01:54:01,000
The Hugh Act had lost its pop by then. They did their damage in the 50s and in the 60s, nobody was really paying attention to them. They had more important things to deal with.

1273
01:54:01,000 --> 01:54:14,000
But I just offer that to show you that we were under surveillance at that time. Another time I went to California to see my sister who was alive at that time living in Los Angeles.

1274
01:54:14,000 --> 01:54:32,000
And I came back and my bag was open. And I wondered what happened in my suitcase. A few days later, Jimmy Hooper, who was ahead of a cour at that time, knew a cour, said, uh-huh, I understand you went to California. I said, how did you know that?

1275
01:54:32,000 --> 01:54:45,000
Because the FBI asked me, what were you doing in California? And I put two and two together. They had searched my bag when I came back because they wanted to see if I was bringing anything in.

1276
01:54:45,000 --> 01:54:59,000
And the third piece of evidence also in 1960. All of this is post-rebellion where I become more than just a yellow sticky.

1277
01:54:59,000 --> 01:55:15,000
I went, I was asked to go on a trip to Europe to look at New Towns based on some groups interest in how they knew I was interested in housing because of the work that I had done with College of Medicine and Dentistry of New Jersey of New Jersey.

1278
01:55:15,000 --> 01:55:42,000
And so I was asked to go kind of as a detail. And so I got my passport and I went. And in France, I ran into this young woman named Jackie. And I was surprised because here she was in France. And here I was in France. And we have this great reunion at this automatic.

1279
01:55:42,000 --> 01:55:57,000
People don't know what an automatic is now, but that's the way that, you know, that was a fast food restaurant of the day. So I'm buying food and this fine lady comes up and she looks at me. I look at her and we had this big reunion in the automatic.

1280
01:55:58,000 --> 01:56:08,000
And everybody's happy, happy, happy. But to make a long story short, we got together later on that day and she started asking me questions about what was I doing in France?

1281
01:56:08,000 --> 01:56:21,000
What was I doing on this trip? Who did I see? What was I doing? Blah blah blah blah blah blah blah blah. And so I'm thinking that, you know, she's attracted to me because I certainly was attracted to her.

1282
01:56:21,000 --> 01:56:45,000
And I'm walking, we're walking down the left bank of the same river. And she just walked on her head. And I said, Jackie, why are you running? Why are you walking so fast? And she just kept walking. And I walked faster. She walked even faster. So at some point, my ego said, I don't need this.

1283
01:56:45,000 --> 01:56:59,000
So she walked on. I've never seen her again. She never contacted me. I put two and two together. She was representing the man and wanted to find out why I was there and what I was doing.

1284
01:56:59,000 --> 01:57:13,000
She got the confirmation that she needed that I was really harmless because I really was there to look at some houses in France, England, two or three other things. Russia, we met in Russia.

1285
01:57:13,000 --> 01:57:22,000
So that's the kind of thing it was. Yes, there was presence all the time. And then laid on. I'm just thinking about this too.

1286
01:57:23,000 --> 01:57:41,000
I got permission to look at Governor Hughes' papers down in Trenton. He and I became friends after College of Medicine and Dentistry of New Jersey of New Jersey. And I asked him, could I take a look at your files because I'm thinking about writing the book.

1287
01:57:41,000 --> 01:58:01,000
I was with Long before I actually wrote anything down. And he gave me permission to look into his files, which was complete with all kinds of stuff from people that I knew who were informing on us to the police. And I was amazed.

1288
01:58:01,000 --> 01:58:04,000
So that's the way it went.

1289
01:58:04,000 --> 01:58:13,000
Yeah, I'm sure you weren't well, let me just check. So 65 to 66 year old. The two academic semesters fall and spring you're up in the night.

1290
01:58:13,000 --> 01:58:29,000
Yeah, right summer 66 here again, right 60s fall 66 up to New Haven spring the new haven. Right. And then summer of 67 back. Yeah. And I'm sure it. Well, you can tell me I'm I'm presuming that it didn't surprise you,

1291
01:58:29,000 --> 01:58:52,000
but were you anticipating open conflict in the streets of Newark NJ? It happened other places already. Yes, everybody was predicting it. And people were just proud of people as a bet as the weather was going to happen and knew at the particular time that it did.

1292
01:58:52,000 --> 01:59:13,000
But I was coming back from Philadelphia from black power conference down there. And I heard it on the turn pipe. I was kind of sleepy, but I woke up then driving my Ford failing. And so I came into the Newark NJ because I heard the city had been sealed off, but we could get in. We knew the streets.

1293
01:59:13,000 --> 01:59:27,000
So I came in and I think I went home that day, but the next day or it could have been that same night. I was in the car with three other guys. I think it was the next night because these people didn't go to Philadelphia with me.

1294
01:59:27,000 --> 01:59:39,000
And we were just riding around looking to see what was going on. And two blocks from here on the street.

1295
01:59:39,000 --> 01:59:52,000
Next to the AME church whose name I will remember in a minute, but I can't right now think it was court street going up a hill. I heard the sirens coming.

1296
01:59:52,000 --> 02:00:02,000
I looked through my rear view mirror and showing up. There was a cop cop bearing down on us. We were out after the curfew. They pulled me over.

1297
02:00:02,000 --> 02:00:15,000
Four guys get out, pistols, shotguns up against the car motherfucker, which of course we did.

1298
02:00:15,000 --> 02:00:30,000
And they searched us, found nothing on us, and then they told me to open the hood. Now fortunately, I had law books that I had forgotten to take out.

1299
02:00:30,000 --> 02:00:41,000
Because it was a tense moment there. And the sergeant said, okay, these guys are law students. Let them go. But the other police didn't want to do that.

1300
02:00:41,000 --> 02:00:49,000
Shotgun man had that gun on all of us at the whole time leaning up against the car. And he wanted to do us.

1301
02:00:49,000 --> 02:01:04,000
Pistol man too. But the sergeant who was supposed to be in charge had to set them again. These are law students. As is to remind them, you're going to have trouble explaining this one if you kill these guys.

1302
02:01:04,000 --> 02:01:26,000
Now the other guys did not were not law students, but I think he was trying to save our lives. So at some point they made a decision, hosted the guns, shot gun down, jumped in the car, torn up the speed turn right at this speed right over here, high speed, and went everywhere they were going next time.

1303
02:01:26,000 --> 02:01:32,000
That was the first time I looked down the wrong end of a shot gun.

1304
02:01:32,000 --> 02:01:46,000
We're back after short break and we swap drives if that is something you want to make note of.

1305
02:01:46,000 --> 02:01:59,000
I'm interested in the following. You had been in Philadelphia for Black Power Conference and you come back and tremendous tumult in the streets five days.

1306
02:01:59,000 --> 02:02:08,000
How did you assess what was happening? How did you think about it? How did you add it up at the time?

1307
02:02:08,000 --> 02:02:23,000
Well, at the time after that first encounter with the police, I tried to stay on the cover as much as I could, especially living with Phil. At some point we just left the house and went somewhere else.

1308
02:02:23,000 --> 02:02:39,000
We went a basement apartment, but I think they might have had the wrong address because that HUAC report has us at 642 High Street, but it was really 624 High Street.

1309
02:02:39,000 --> 02:02:55,000
That might be significant, just some bad policing on their part. I saw a whole lot of stuff. I saw people happy to be destroying, happy to turn the tide.

1310
02:02:55,000 --> 02:03:05,000
I knew something was going to happen and showing up when the police came into town, when the state police and the National Guard came in, things changed.

1311
02:03:05,000 --> 02:03:11,000
It was doing that second period that the police rioted, especially the state police.

1312
02:03:11,000 --> 02:03:25,000
At the time I was in charge of a group of law student vistas and we were working on a housing project. How do we stop urban renewal and we were investigating the whole relocation process?

1313
02:03:25,000 --> 02:03:43,000
That's what eventually we cited to do some serious damage to that urban renewal machine. But we stopped doing that to go interview witnesses to the police violence. That's when I really saw what the damage had been.

1314
02:03:43,000 --> 02:04:00,000
My law students took information, I remember one, there was a bar in the south ward where two young men had come in after the thing had been looted and we're still looking for whatever they could find.

1315
02:04:00,000 --> 02:04:11,000
The state cops rolled up on them. They couldn't get out. One of them hid and the other one said, okay, I'm here.

1316
02:04:11,000 --> 02:04:21,000
The cops said, what do we have here? This is based on the witness that I interviewed. And then they just began to systematically shoot it.

1317
02:04:21,000 --> 02:04:29,000
And they shot him 40 sometimes, including in the top of his head, after he fell into the floor.

1318
02:04:29,000 --> 02:04:39,000
So we took that information down and we thought somebody was going to do something about it because there were stories like that coming in from all over the place.

1319
02:04:39,000 --> 02:04:50,000
And after Newark Rebellion was over once Oliver Lofton and Animate Shepherd from the Legal Services Project, that's where I was working.

1320
02:04:50,000 --> 02:05:02,000
I took all this information and turned it over to the authorities. I was called before Grand jury and one of the questions was,

1321
02:05:02,000 --> 02:05:28,000
well, he was a part of the government's deterrent. I didn't tell you. Amiri Amiri Baraka found out, Emiri Amiri Amiri Baraka found out about this particular incident and sent a photographer to Perry's, no, to one of the funeral homes and took pictures of the corpse, which was destroyed as you can imagine.

1322
02:05:28,000 --> 02:05:36,000
And then he made a flyer and put it all out over town. Is this what we're going to allow to happen to all young people in town? Something worse to that effect.

1323
02:05:36,000 --> 02:05:57,000
So when the Grand jury, when I was called in for the Grand jury, they asked me, didn't I think it was inflammatory to pass that fly around? I said, well, first of all, I didn't pass the fly around. But second of all, don't you think it was inflammatory that the man was shot 46 times, including the type of his head?

1324
02:05:57,000 --> 02:06:04,000
So now I'm a smart ally. They didn't like me, but it was nothing they could do about it because they knew it was true.

1325
02:06:04,000 --> 02:06:17,000
So as the time went by during the actual time of Newark Rebellion, it would just became more and more stories like that and people were really whipped.

1326
02:06:18,000 --> 02:06:28,000
But as it turned out, the power structure was really scared of what was happening. There was a woman named Louise Epperson.

1327
02:06:28,000 --> 02:06:38,000
I wish she were alive so that you can interview her. But she was a person who was a homeowner, working class woman who was a homeowner, a district leader,

1328
02:06:38,000 --> 02:06:52,000
and a central ward right up the street here whose house was in the path of the proposed College of Medicine and Dentistry of New Jersey, which at that time was supposed to take 200 acres of land.

1329
02:06:52,000 --> 02:07:06,000
And she was organizing homeowners against it. And she said when interviewed before Newark Rebellion, I couldn't get anybody to talk to me.

1330
02:07:06,000 --> 02:07:19,000
But after Newark Rebellion, she had this twinkling eye. Everybody wanted to talk to me. So was that kind of experience? So feeling I said, well we got to do something about that.

1331
02:07:19,000 --> 02:07:32,000
We got a caption bottle, some of that energy that's now running in our favor. The tide has temporarily turned and our favor despite all the violence which nobody wanted.

1332
02:07:32,000 --> 02:07:42,000
What can we do with that image of that black man with that brick? What can we do to turn things around and make things better?

1333
02:07:42,000 --> 02:07:52,000
I'll have all of that. Actually before I say that next question, can you say a word about Amiri Amiri Baraka as United Brothers?

1334
02:07:52,000 --> 02:08:06,000
Well, the United Brothers was formed. I think the letter came out in December of 1967.

1335
02:08:06,000 --> 02:08:19,000
Amiri Amiri Baraka came back to Newark NJ because he was born and raised here in 1965. But then he went out to California and met Ron Karenga.

1336
02:08:19,000 --> 02:08:29,000
He became very much influenced by what Karinga was doing in Los Angeles with his group called Us, just U Capital U Capital S.

1337
02:08:29,000 --> 02:08:40,000
And he wanted to do something like that here. But he had another concept of mind of electing a black man because this was a majority town.

1338
02:08:40,000 --> 02:08:56,000
And he understood the whole concept of a black United Front better than most of us did. He'd been in New York and then on the front line with a lot of people who were thinking thoughts that we just weren't thinking at that particular time.

1339
02:08:56,000 --> 02:09:04,000
And he was in a position to do that because when during Newark Rebellion, he was beaten badly by the cops.

1340
02:09:04,000 --> 02:09:10,000
He had a national reputation, but not that many people knew him here except the people he grew up with.

1341
02:09:10,000 --> 02:09:22,000
He was doing his own work with the arts just as we were doing our work and each of us in our own little belly work.

1342
02:09:22,000 --> 02:09:39,000
He was doing his with the arts in a group called the Spirit House Movers. But when he got beaten and the cameras went all over him, his name became much bigger than it was.

1343
02:09:39,000 --> 02:09:50,000
And so he then and then the black power conference came about during the last days of Newark Rebellion anyway.

1344
02:09:50,000 --> 02:09:57,000
And folks said, well, you need to stop that. And they said they're not going to stop it. Wright was his name. Forget his first name.

1345
02:09:57,000 --> 02:10:08,000
Wright was the guy's name who was in charge of that. And Amiri Amiri Baraka became the keynote speaker at that particular event.

1346
02:10:08,000 --> 02:10:16,000
And from that point forward, he was the man. So he was in a position to call together a lot of people.

1347
02:10:16,000 --> 02:10:23,000
Most of whom were his friends from college. I mean, not from college, but from high school and other growing up here in New York.

1348
02:10:23,000 --> 02:10:29,000
And he included some of us who at that point had taken on a leadership position.

1349
02:10:29,000 --> 02:10:40,000
My position was as I told you before, I was just a soldier in the army until after Newark Rebellion, when we resurrected College of Medicine and Dentistry of New Jersey of New Jersey.

1350
02:10:40,000 --> 02:10:57,000
We resurrected a fight that had really been lost because the community had come together in the spring of 1967 to demonstrate at City Hall about this medical school proposed.

1351
02:10:57,000 --> 02:11:10,000
There was a lawsuit and they lost the lawsuit based, which was based upon the and incompletion of testimony at the, at the blight hearings to determine whether the land should be taken.

1352
02:11:10,000 --> 02:11:20,000
So they lost that. But during that time, I mean, the Colonel Hassan Jeru-Ahmed had, some of his people had taken, knocked the books out of the hand of the clerk.

1353
02:11:20,000 --> 02:11:25,000
And the people said, whoa, so everybody started coming to see what was going to happen next.

1354
02:11:25,000 --> 02:11:38,000
So it became, he became a cause of labor and the event became a cause of labor. And it was said that College of Medicine and Dentistry of New Jersey of New Jersey was one of the reasons for Newark Rebellion.

1355
02:11:38,000 --> 02:11:48,000
So I had nothing to do with any of that. I was in the audience sometime when that happened one or two times when it happened because I came down and saw it from New Haven.

1356
02:11:48,000 --> 02:12:01,000
But I wasn't anywhere near the leadership of that. But when after Newark Rebellion, still and I put together this organization called the Newark Area Planning Association, NAPA, NAPA.

1357
02:12:01,000 --> 02:12:08,000
And I had been in New Haven and talked to some of my friends at the planning and architectural school.

1358
02:12:08,000 --> 02:12:14,000
And I said that medical school was too large. And we started talking about an alternative plan.

1359
02:12:14,000 --> 02:12:23,000
The idea was they would build a massive footprint through urban clearance. 160 acres was a proposal.

1360
02:12:23,000 --> 02:12:32,000
I was 200 and then it was brought down to 180. And so I asked the planners, up in Yale, what's the smallest footprint you can give us?

1361
02:12:32,000 --> 02:12:45,000
And they said, well, we can use American medical school associates, American medical associates and standards. And we can give you a 19 acre footprint, how by going up.

1362
02:12:45,000 --> 02:13:00,000
So that became a rallying cry for the new opposition. So my little office over on the corner of South Orange and Bruce Street, which was an old candy store which had no heat and hot water.

1363
02:13:00,000 --> 02:13:18,000
We had a press conference. In addition to that, I had gotten in touch with the Legal Defense Fund. And the Legal Defense Fund said they would handle the case. So Jack Greenberg sent over a young man who was our lawyer.

1364
02:13:19,000 --> 02:13:36,000
The law, the complaint was going to be made to HUD and the H.E.W. based on the insufficiency of housing. The research for which had been done by me and my vistas this summer before and into 1967.

1365
02:13:37,000 --> 02:13:56,000
So based upon that research, we knew there was a 1% available vacancy rate in Newark NJ, which meant on anyone given day only 1% of the houses were available. But they were driving people out of their homes that they were already in so much so that there was no way they could possibly accommodate all those people.

1366
02:13:56,000 --> 02:14:17,000
So with a combination of the lawsuit and an alternate plan, we revised College of Medicine and Dentistry of New Jersey of New Jersey and I became a leader. So in December of 1967, before we even began the negotiations, which ended up in success for the community, Amiri Baraka asked me to become a part of the United Brothers.

1367
02:14:17,000 --> 02:14:27,000
The United Brothers was a group that was formed for the purposes of pulling together the community to elect the first black man. That's how we got started.

1368
02:14:27,000 --> 02:14:37,000
How did you swing in practice? How did you swing the successful negotiation through NAPA on the 68th Christmas public housing and job creation?

1369
02:14:37,000 --> 02:14:45,000
Well, it wasn't just NAPA. it was also the committee against Negro and Puerto Rican removal, which Miss Epperson had headed.

1370
02:14:45,000 --> 02:14:59,000
And she had other people who were from the ordinary, regular political persuasion folks who were involved in that with her. And I had the new breed with me in NAPA.

1371
02:14:59,000 --> 02:15:12,000
So together we had a coalition going into it. So we said, you got to sit down and talk to us. We said to the government, he had us down to his place and all that to Morven. and OK. So we were going to talk.

1372
02:15:12,000 --> 02:15:28,000
So we set up negotiations. And negotiations were based on the belief that they were going to let people come in and quote unquote have their say and then they were going to probably throw us a bone and the band would play on.

1373
02:15:28,000 --> 02:15:41,000
But we said no, we have a negotiating team. We have a nine person negotiating team. Three from NAPA, three from the committee against Negro and Puerto Rican removal and three from other organizations.

1374
02:15:41,000 --> 02:15:48,000
So they said, well, what about everybody else? And then we had an audience of about 200 people, most of my all supporters.

1375
02:15:48,000 --> 02:16:03,000
And one by one people just stood up and said, well, I want to say I want to be a part of the negotiate. We shut them up. We would not let them talk with the support of the 200 people Harry wheel and I just wolfed them down.

1376
02:16:03,000 --> 02:16:21,000
I mean, I can't explain it any other way. We shut them up. They had no way to go. So the people on the other side of the table who were representing the government of the commission of the new commission of the Department of Community Affairs, which was new, man named Paul N. Ylvisaker, who became my friend as well.

1377
02:16:21,000 --> 02:16:36,000
Ralph A. Dungan who was the head of the New Jersey Department of Higher Education and various other people who worked for them. They said, well, okay.

1378
02:16:36,000 --> 02:16:52,000
Over the period of months, we negotiated an agreement. And we had done our research. We had our supporters from Yale, of course, but we also brought in other people who were experts on affirmative action hiring.

1379
02:16:52,000 --> 02:17:14,000
We had people on housing. We had people on health. We had all so we negotiated what's been called in medical school agreements. And that's where we got 60 acres of land for vacant urban renewal land for housing, which was done by nonprofit groups here, headed by a housing council, which we set up, which Iran eventually about a year later that happened.

1380
02:17:14,000 --> 02:17:33,000
We said we want the model cities program. We want to have that group set up as who was set up as the advisory committee. We want that whole group thrown out because there was the mayor's buddies in henchmen. And we had an election. I was elected to that along with other people. We had that covered.

1381
02:17:33,000 --> 02:18:01,000
We wanted a, we wanted to set up a training program for blacks and Latinos to get the construction jobs because they were going to say, we don't have anybody. So yeah, you're right because you being discriminated against us for years, we're going to train them. And they said, okay. And we had a group of people brought together the name of which I forget at this point.

1382
02:18:01,000 --> 02:18:14,000
But it was a group of all the stakeholders in the jobs. We had the unions, we had the contractors association, we had the city, we had the housing authority, we had people from the community.

1383
02:18:14,000 --> 02:18:29,000
They met regularly to see what kind of compliance there was going on. That's the key thing. We had an entity that we set up to make sure they did what they promised to do at that table.

1384
02:18:29,000 --> 02:18:43,000
And all the time, the concept of that invisible brother with the brick was right there with us to let them know that if you mess with us now, you got to pay for it later. Now we never said that, but that was in their minds.

1385
02:18:43,000 --> 02:18:50,000
Now it's time went by that lesson and lessons and lessons and lessons, but we got as much as we could out of it.

1386
02:18:51,000 --> 02:18:58,000
You would contribute your efforts to the campaign of Kenneth A. Gibson.

1387
02:18:58,000 --> 02:19:02,000
Yes. You're like the Nolux First Black Mary. I was his first campaign manager.

1388
02:19:02,000 --> 02:19:06,000
1970, yeah.

1389
02:19:06,000 --> 02:19:18,000
So you've been through 67. You've had the reach the agreement in 68, which probably you can tell me how you evaluated that in terms of how encompassing your success was in that.

1390
02:19:18,000 --> 02:19:22,000
And it sounds like you managed pretty well to achieve some very substantive results.

1391
02:19:22,000 --> 02:19:30,000
Yeah. The only thing is we had to fight within the community to make sure that the results really were substantial.

1392
02:19:30,000 --> 02:19:37,000
Because if you're looking at a land here, we had 60 acres of land. All kinds of people came out of the woodwork and wanted that land.

1393
02:19:37,000 --> 02:19:49,000
But at that point, the white controllers were standing around watching the black folks fight each other saying, made it better man win.

1394
02:19:49,000 --> 02:19:57,000
And we hope it's not Williams. But we want. We established the housing council and we decided who was going to get the land.

1395
02:19:57,000 --> 02:20:03,000
So right now there's a thousand units of housing around that the housing council determines.

1396
02:20:03,000 --> 02:20:09,000
They didn't want the new construction trades training corporation to succeed.

1397
02:20:09,000 --> 02:20:21,000
But hundreds of young men were successful and getting a union books because we fought the unions, we fought the state, we fought the local folks to make sure that happens.

1398
02:20:21,000 --> 02:20:31,000
People Gus Henningburg was involved in that George Fontaine was involved in that Jim Walker those were the people who handled that part of we back them up.

1399
02:20:31,000 --> 02:20:48,000
They backed us up when we needed it. So those were the two most exciting. And of course the model cities election produced a whole new set of characters that hadn't happened before, including myself to become involved with a federal program of that magnitude was just 5.6 million dollars.

1400
02:20:48,000 --> 02:20:59,000
And we had a joint veto. If we didn't like what the city wanted, we could veto. And of course if they didn't like what we wanted, they could be to all of this came out of the agreement.

1401
02:20:59,000 --> 02:21:05,000
I don't think we had that anywhere else in the country.

1402
02:21:05,000 --> 02:21:15,000
The Houston's elected in 1970 obviously they're close to the mayor. What's your feeling about how you managed through the late 60s?

1403
02:21:15,000 --> 02:21:27,000
Where you stood at that point and how did you feel about prospects for the change in kind of building the world you were trying to build?

1404
02:21:27,000 --> 02:21:41,000
Well I was high on the results of College of Medicine and Dentistry of New Jersey of New Jersey what we were doing at the time in the street. The street organizations that we had the fact that it wasn't a democratic party group.

1405
02:21:41,000 --> 02:21:54,000
It was not just them alone. We had some of them with us. But the real momentum for this thing came from the people from our civil rights and black power groups that they put gifts in an office.

1406
02:21:54,000 --> 02:22:06,000
And I think he knew that. He said that success in the years that have followed. But when I got the job and he had promised me the job earlier, I think.

1407
02:22:06,000 --> 02:22:14,000
And I was happy he lived up to that. I learned the potential in the job from being on the model city's neighborhood council.

1408
02:22:14,000 --> 02:22:26,000
And I learned how that particular position was what I wanted if he won. So he won. And so I was in charge with planning most of the federal money that was coming to the town, which was substantial.

1409
02:22:26,000 --> 02:22:35,000
I was 26 years old at that time. I was making $26,000. That made a whole lot of people mad at least raise some people's eyebrows.

1410
02:22:35,000 --> 02:22:47,000
So there was a lot of an attempt by our part to continue what we had started in the street just to bring it into the streets.

1411
02:22:47,000 --> 02:22:54,000
We wanted to make sure there was democracy for the people in the city and that they got the best of whatever was possible.

1412
02:22:54,000 --> 02:22:58,000
So that was what was in our mind. Because that's what we grew up on.

1413
02:22:58,000 --> 02:23:12,000
Amiri Baraka, I believe, wanted that as well. But see, Amiri Baraka had a big heavy organization at that time called Committee for a Unified Newark, which was the main group that pulled the folks together to put Gibson in office.

1414
02:23:12,000 --> 02:23:24,000
But it was a cultural nationalist group. A lot of people didn't like cultural nationalism, including me. I didn't think that I thought it was somewhat artificial to go and say we're going to speak Swahili.

1415
02:23:24,000 --> 02:23:34,000
And then put on West African garb and we were all supposed to be there for legitimate. And anybody who wasn't doing that was illegitimate. I didn't believe that.

1416
02:23:34,000 --> 02:23:45,000
Because at the time, I liked the way jeans and I liked the book jobs, which I don't do now. But at that time, I thought I was just as black as anybody else.

1417
02:23:45,000 --> 02:23:55,000
So there was that conflict within the community that Gibson took advantage of to a certain extent.

1418
02:23:55,000 --> 02:24:09,000
Because he was not really one of us. He was kind of like there. But he really was not on the front line of most of these struggles.

1419
02:24:09,000 --> 02:24:23,000
He came in kind of like after the battle was over. And if you needed somebody, for example, he was the vice president of the business industrial coordinate council, which came out of the barren's fight.

1420
02:24:23,000 --> 02:24:30,000
And he helped get some jobs. Okay. So he was in. He was not an event guard. He was kind of like in the second tier.

1421
02:24:30,000 --> 02:24:52,000
So that was his, his, his MO and perhaps we needed somebody like that because he wasn't so controversial. But then when, when we got into City Hall, and I say we advised it because when he got into City Hall, he did not want people like me or Amiri Baraka and any kind of leadership position.

1422
02:24:52,000 --> 02:25:03,000
So he handled us in two different ways. Me, I work for him. So eventually he fired me because his people told him that I could not be trusted. I was going to take his job.

1423
02:25:03,000 --> 02:25:21,000
But all I did was make him look good. Because from that $5.6 million that I raised with the money, I was just from, I doubled that plus brought in the best, what the hood called the best housing redevelopment process housing rehabilitation project in the country called project rehab, which was another

1424
02:25:21,000 --> 02:25:36,000
$15 million in mortgage. So eventually he found a reason to fire me, which was based on an audit and all audit, which was dug up by a man who was running for office.

1425
02:25:36,000 --> 02:25:46,000
And they said, heard questions, $300,000. Well, heard had questioned that a year before he brought it out. And we were in process of answering those questions.

1426
02:25:46,000 --> 02:26:03,000
And it was really nothing missing what had happened was we had interpreted the guidelines one way and other people had interpreted the other way, namely the people in the Gibson administration who didn't want me there.

1427
02:26:03,000 --> 02:26:26,000
So I can tell you about those inventions man, we went to war with the Rep. Joseph G. Minish. I had an opportunity. Minish was in the front page of the star ledger advertising his false claim with his little subtle reference that I had stolen the money without really saying that.

1428
02:26:26,000 --> 02:26:43,000
And of course the people said, oh yeah, we told you, we told you, we told you, you can't put them in there. They're going to steal the money. A lot of my friends were even saying that. So then I came back, I went over to see Mort Pye who's the editor of the star ledger.

1429
02:26:43,000 --> 02:26:54,000
And I said to Mort Pye, you have done me a disservice because up to this point you have not listened to what I said. This is over the telephone I told him that.

1430
02:26:54,000 --> 02:27:12,000
And so he asked me to explain. So I explained to him what was going on. And he paused for a moment. He said, bring me down what you had. So I brought him an article. And I knew how to write press releases. I brought him the article stating what our responses had already been to the audit.

1431
02:27:12,000 --> 02:27:30,000
And he ran that front pages on Wednesday. All of this other stuff was Saturday and Sunday following Wednesday. I got front page. So then some of my friends came back and said, oh, now we're seeing what you're saying. Yeah, yeah, you're not too bad after all.

1432
02:27:30,000 --> 02:27:48,000
But Gibson didn't like that. So as I was gaining more and more support, I was on television. I was on a on this guy's show. I forget the guy's name, but it was equivalent of a Jerry spring on type show where he comes on and vilifies the people.

1433
02:27:48,000 --> 02:27:57,000
So I was on and he was asking what he thought were hard questions. And I was just giving him back the right answer. And so he said at the end, you know, Mr. Williams.

1434
02:27:57,000 --> 02:28:09,000
They're good guys and they're bad guys. And I've decided and it was a pause because he's got this rabbit audience all around him that you are a good guy.

1435
02:28:09,000 --> 02:28:26,000
The audience explodes. Yeah, yeah, yeah, yeah, yeah, yeah, yeah, yeah, yeah. He comes up shakes my hand. I'm standing there smiling. My father's grin. And so the whole thing turned around.

1436
02:28:26,000 --> 02:28:34,000
And so Gibson at one point called me and oh, yeah, there was a yeah, yeah, yeah, yeah, you're finished.

1437
02:28:34,000 --> 02:28:48,000
Because I said at that point in the newspaper, I said, minutes was just setting me up as a scapegoat. So minutes had to respond to that. And he says, okay, so I'm going to have a hearing. So he called the hearing.

1438
02:28:48,000 --> 02:28:59,000
This was before the TV experiences, I think he called the hearing and it was a tie. I mean, he had his guy come out and say that I was wrong. I had my own notes which said I was right.

1439
02:28:59,000 --> 02:29:12,000
So, you know, when you get a U.S. congressman into a tie in a public form, you're doing pretty good. But one thing was very clear. You asked me how I was what my what I noticed.

1440
02:29:12,000 --> 02:29:28,000
My controller was not there with me. He had been told by many people don't show up because they thought I needed him to get the information.

1441
02:29:28,000 --> 02:29:42,000
Hello, I'm a lawyer. I had been wrestling with this thing. I knew this stuff inside and outside. And everything he threw at me. I threw right back at him.

1442
02:29:42,000 --> 02:29:50,000
Even with nobody there on my set. None of my staff showed up my director. My deputy director didn't show up. Nobody showed up. I was there by myself.

1443
02:29:50,000 --> 02:30:07,000
So then after that, and after the television series Gibson calls me in and says, I want you to resign. I said, why? He said, because of the audit. I said, well, by this time I know you don't want me but I want time to answer and respond and get this thing out of the way.

1444
02:30:07,000 --> 02:30:16,000
And then I'll leave because I had planned on leaving anyway. I didn't want to be there anymore. And he said, no, you can't do that. I'll give you 30 days. Make a few months.

1445
02:30:16,000 --> 02:30:31,000
So during that 30 days, I collected all the documents that I had that I knew I needed because I thought somebody else was going to come after me with an indictment, which they never did. And I'm going to tell you why in a minute.

1446
02:30:31,000 --> 02:30:46,000
And so he called me in at the end of the 30 days and fired me. Now there was one more incident in that too because I was going to have a rally. And I expected four or five hundred people to come out to run a minute out of town and he told me, don't do it.

1447
02:30:46,000 --> 02:30:56,000
And I said, I'm going to do it. The mayor told me that to an intermediary. Of course, he didn't have a guts. He didn't have a ball to tell me this himself.

1448
02:30:56,000 --> 02:31:09,000
And so the intermediary came back and said, anybody who on your staff who goes to that rally would be fired. So I told my people to get the word out, but they showed up anyway. Most of them showed up anyway.

1449
02:31:09,000 --> 02:31:23,000
Not my top staff, but the little people showed up anyway. I had 400 people in Raymond A. Brown with the main speaker asking why wasn't the man here, Raymond A. Brown, the famous lawyer who had been the one who got Amiri Amiri Baraka out.

1450
02:31:23,000 --> 02:31:30,000
And who got a lot of other people off because of his excellent legal presentation.

1451
02:31:30,000 --> 02:31:37,000
He said, why in the mayor here and why is he trying to get rid of Williams. So anyway, the mayor had the power. He got rid of me.

1452
02:31:37,000 --> 02:31:47,000
So I went on to set up my law practice, but about a year later, maybe a few months later, I'm on my way to Washington for some reason. I get off the old Eastern shuttling.

1453
02:31:47,000 --> 02:32:04,000
And there's this little man who comes up to me and starts talking, Mr. Williams, you don't know me. But I was one of the auditors when you were the director of the Marvel series program. So I immediately stiffened.

1454
02:32:04,000 --> 02:32:19,000
And this guy says, he's a little guy. He says, the prosecutor came to me and asked me, was there anything there to indict this man on?

1455
02:32:19,000 --> 02:32:32,000
And I told him, and no one's heard in terms. There is nothing there. He turned around, walked back into the crowd, and I've never seen him since then.

1456
02:32:32,000 --> 02:32:45,000
True story. So that's what happened to me with this great new city experience. I was not able to apply all of the skills that I wanted to. I was able to do some things.

1457
02:32:45,000 --> 02:32:52,000
Amiri Baraka had a similar experience with some housing. He was trying to build, but that's a whole different story. I'll let him tell his own story.

1458
02:32:52,000 --> 02:33:02,000
And the mayor flopped him up with that. And as a result, he lost all of the programs that he was trying to do, including building that housing.

1459
02:33:02,000 --> 02:33:15,000
And he just kind of put cultural nationalism aside and decided he was going to be a Marxist. He said, I'm a communist now. And so people made that abrupt turn. A lot of people couldn't go with him.

1460
02:33:15,000 --> 02:33:33,000
So now he is still just as famous as he was ever was as a writer and as a playwright and a poet. But he was after that point out of the mainstream and Gibson with his non progressive politics was able to reign supreme.

1461
02:33:33,000 --> 02:33:36,000
Let's take a break and then we'll come back and finish up.

1462
02:33:36,000 --> 02:33:38,000
All right.

1463
02:33:38,000 --> 02:33:49,000
We're back on after short break. And I want to as we sort of look to the years beyond the early 70s, I'd really like to have you touch on a couple things.

1464
02:33:49,000 --> 02:34:02,000
One is your election for the National Bar Association presidency, 78. Youngest person ever elected to that role. Of course, that's the group that is the black analog to the ABA in the longest

1465
02:34:02,000 --> 02:34:12,000
history of discrimination, exclusion, and the latter organization. I want to hear about the love that have you sort of framed your mayoral race in 82.

1466
02:34:12,000 --> 02:34:15,000
And let me just leave those two things with you.

1467
02:34:15,000 --> 02:34:17,000
Okay.

1468
02:34:18,000 --> 02:34:34,000
Well, I went into practice in law after I left City Hall. Well, I just couldn't practice law. I mean, it was like, how are you going to keep them down on the farm after they've seen Perry, you know?

1469
02:34:34,000 --> 02:34:53,000
So I ran into a friend named O. T. Wells, who I had met at Harvard when I was speaking there. I was my own city director. He was president elect of the National Bar Association.

1470
02:34:53,000 --> 02:35:06,000
And he convinced me that I should play a prominent part in the National Bar Association. I believe I had gone to one meeting, one convention before that. And he invited me to be his guest.

1471
02:35:06,000 --> 02:35:17,000
So I became a part of it. He appointed me as assistant regional director, which was really something he just dreamed up wasn't in the Constitution.

1472
02:35:17,000 --> 02:35:30,000
And make a long story short because of some foul up in Los Angeles, the following summer. His convention couldn't be there. And he had no one to plan his convention. There was no staff at the NBA at that time.

1473
02:35:30,000 --> 02:35:37,000
So he said, Jr. I want you to plan my convention. It's going to be in San Francisco. Go do it.

1474
02:35:37,000 --> 02:35:53,000
So I started calling people all over the country. My dime, my time. Lawyers that he had given me the names of other people had or people I heard of. And I put together a great invention for him, if I'm going to say so myself, but he also agreed.

1475
02:35:53,000 --> 02:36:10,000
And I met a lot of people along the way. So that was my, my, my organizational basis, if you will. And so by the time I came to his convention, which was in San Francisco in 1973.

1476
02:36:10,000 --> 02:36:14,000
Yes.

1477
02:36:14,000 --> 02:36:25,000
There were other issues that had to be dealt with. There were a lot of young lawyers, especially women lawyers who were dissatisfied with the way the ball was going at that time.

1478
02:36:25,000 --> 02:36:36,000
And we who had been in the movement or who had been influenced by the movement were steeped in the tradition of democracy. We wanted people to be involved in a lot of decisions that they weren't.

1479
02:36:36,000 --> 02:36:49,000
The National Bar Association was kind of like an imperial potentate kind of arrangement. You, the president, you the man. You did what you damn well, please.

1480
02:36:49,000 --> 02:36:57,000
So we elected two things happened at time, visa video, young lawyers. We elected a new treasurer.

1481
02:36:57,000 --> 02:37:06,000
I think you joined up from Florida, the lawyer from Florida. And I became elected to the board at that, at that particular time.

1482
02:37:06,000 --> 02:37:20,000
Now that was, that was a, that was the first two things. But we also, I also revised along with some friends. We revived the young lawyers division, which had been started once, but had died down.

1483
02:37:20,000 --> 02:37:32,000
We revived that. That was our vehicle. And I drew upon the knowledge I had that the people around the country that I had been calling, some of whom were young, some of whom were not so young to make that organization very viable.

1484
02:37:32,000 --> 02:37:44,000
So to make a long story short, we became, the young lawyers became a campaign enterprise for young and aspiring lawyers who wanted to see some change come about.

1485
02:37:44,000 --> 02:37:56,000
To make the bar more interested in issues than just, than just conspicuous consumption amongst some very prominent black attorneys as it had become.

1486
02:37:56,000 --> 02:38:08,000
So the next year in Chicago, I ran for fourth vice president. Then the next year, somewhere I ran for third vice president. And then second vice president. And it was time for me to run for president elect.

1487
02:38:08,000 --> 02:38:18,000
Nobody ran against me because I had the young lawyers as a basis plus the women lawyers. Because I believe the women lawyers in 74 were formed. And it was like a complete overlap.

1488
02:38:18,000 --> 02:38:28,000
Because the women who were in the women's division were also in the young lawyers division. So we always had a coalition.

1489
02:38:28,000 --> 02:38:42,000
And we were able to go into each of the large delegations. And we were off a trade-offs. You support our candidates. We support yours.

1490
02:38:42,000 --> 02:38:58,000
So that's that way I parlayed my way up to becoming president elect. And so in Florida of 1978, I became the youngest person ever elected to the National Bar Association because I was only 34 years old.

1491
02:38:58,000 --> 02:39:16,000
And immediately we began to do things on a collective basis. The most important thing was to introduce to the National Bar Association the whole concept of the freedom, the independence of southern Africa.

1492
02:39:16,000 --> 02:39:28,000
So they had never done that before. One of my friends from SNCC was very influential in this next move.

1493
02:39:28,000 --> 02:39:44,000
We knew that the races in southern Rhodesia were trying to prop able moves of wear up as the next God coming for African independence.

1494
02:39:44,000 --> 02:39:55,000
But they really weren't going to give them any independence. The Constitution really kept all the power for the whites. And everybody knew that. But we were lawyers and we knew how to say it.

1495
02:39:55,000 --> 02:40:03,000
So my international affairs committee dissected that and did a very wonderful paper.

1496
02:40:03,000 --> 02:40:21,000
The guy who is now the head of the NAACP Legal Defense Fund was the head of that committee whose name I just cannot think of. This is terrible going into historical record. I couldn't think of his name.

1497
02:40:21,000 --> 02:40:39,000
No, Theodore M. Shaw was not. Theodore M. Shaw was gone before that. It was Julius LeVonne Chambers and I think Elaine R. Jones, Theodore M. Shaw. And now this guy, John, John, he'll come to me in a minute. Sorry, John.

1498
02:40:39,000 --> 02:40:56,000
So the committee, you know, otherwise, you know, it was a very legally scholarly document. And we knew we had something. But it was just going to be another document. So I call my friends from SNCC.

1499
02:40:56,000 --> 02:41:13,000
And I asked, can we get this before the United Nations, African group, the organization of African unity. So we were able to go to the United Nations.

1500
02:41:13,000 --> 02:41:33,000
The organization heard what we had to say. There was a rush for copies. Not only did the OAU accepted. But it was adopted by the General Council of the United Nations as an official document of the United Nations only question of independence for Zimbabwe.

1501
02:41:33,000 --> 02:41:54,000
And it was translated into seven languages and sent all around the world. Friend of mine from Ghana, sent me an article, front page, lead article in the Ghanaian Times, black lawyers, champion, Africa rights or something like that. So it was, it was like my movement days were coming true.

1502
02:41:54,000 --> 02:42:16,000
You know, here we were involved with African independence as African Americans. And for a long time, there was a great deal of unity between the Africans who were in the United Nations and eventually the ones in Washington who were diplomats of a higher level as everybody sought that paper.

1503
02:42:16,000 --> 02:42:29,000
I went to Jamaica, but another one of the United Nations committees and everybody wanted a copy. I got invited to Cuba because of that paper, which I eventually did a year later.

1504
02:42:29,000 --> 02:42:56,000
I had an idea to bring lawyers and doctors and nurses and pharmacists, not pharmacists, dentists to Zimbabwe. That got shot down because the Zimbabwean ambassador when Zimbabwe did become independent. They were very grateful for what I had done, what we had done.

1505
02:42:57,000 --> 02:43:06,000
He didn't call me back in time for me to get this forward grant that I had set up for Vice President.

1506
02:43:06,000 --> 02:43:17,000
Says, Mr. Williams, this thing is going to die unless we get the Zimbabwe government to agree and he never got back to me. So that they didn't want it. He just didn't see the importance of this whole thing.

1507
02:43:18,000 --> 02:43:33,000
So the good part of it was that I was able to parlay this paper on behalf of the NBA into a position where black lawyers could really help in the independence of Zimbabwe.

1508
02:43:33,000 --> 02:43:46,000
And here's the crowning achievement was my people in the White House got the document to Jimmy Carter and got him to hold on to sanctions because of the document. That's what we were told.

1509
02:43:46,000 --> 02:43:58,000
So that was probably the most significant aspects of what I did when I was president. That movement connection was there because we were able to organize the people.

1510
02:43:59,000 --> 02:44:12,000
But also we always kept our focus with our eyes on the prize. Right after that. So that was over in 1979 had a great convention in Los Angeles.

1511
02:44:13,000 --> 02:44:26,000
And for my keynote speaker I had Louis Farrakhan, who wild and mesmerized the people that was a hush when I walked down the aisle with him to bring him into the first plenary session.

1512
02:44:26,000 --> 02:44:40,000
I had met him in New Haven when I was up there. He was the Muslim minister in charge of the mosque there. That's another story. But he wild him. He spoke for about an hour and everybody gave him about.

1513
02:44:40,000 --> 02:44:49,000
And it was the most of the been at least 10 standing novations when he got finished. He was he had everybody in the palm of his hand.

1514
02:44:49,000 --> 02:45:05,000
So that's how I went out next year. I went to Cuba the following year. I went to Harvard for the I call Paul oversoil who was my friend from state here in New Jersey.

1515
02:45:05,000 --> 02:45:12,000
And if you remember from College of Medicine and Dentistry of New Jersey of New Jersey he was then the dean of the education school. So he said I got something for you.

1516
02:45:12,000 --> 02:45:20,000
I said I'm tired and eat something to do. So he got me in Institute of Politics at the John F. Kennedy School of Government, Harvard for a semester.

1517
02:45:20,000 --> 02:45:34,000
So I was beginning to believe that I've been along there. I told him Miami riot occurred. I wrote an article for the New York Times. I wrote an op-ed pace. That was my first op-ed peace anywhere.

1518
02:45:34,000 --> 02:45:44,000
And that kind of brought me back to earth. So I said I got to use all these skills and the talents I have to go back to New York and what can I do?

1519
02:45:44,000 --> 02:46:02,000
Gibson had been there for then going on 12 years. Very little had changed. He had not used the power in the street to match that power which he had in the suite to force any kind of real change.

1520
02:46:02,000 --> 02:46:15,000
For example he's raising taxes. The state was not giving enough money. Kind of like it is right now. So here he was saying I'll take whatever the state will allow and still begging for money from the Fed.

1521
02:46:15,000 --> 02:46:31,000
And it wasn't coming because now we were in the age of Reaganomics. So the power of the people was divorced from the power of the institutions that we had created an entree to.

1522
02:46:31,000 --> 02:46:51,000
They had English but you got the point. So I wanted to correct that. And I wanted to create another movement to get me in there so that I could make sure that the independent organizations that had been killed by Gibson could be revived.

1523
02:46:51,000 --> 02:47:03,000
And we could once again get the kind of power we needed to back up the folks who had been elected and put into office. Obviously I didn't win.

1524
02:47:03,000 --> 02:47:14,000
I didn't have the money he had. There were other people running to I didn't have anywhere near the money that was necessary. People told me I should have run for council first but I thought the time was now City Council.

1525
02:47:14,000 --> 02:47:24,000
I thought the time was now and once I got involved in that whole process and I saw what you needed to do to raise money. I realized that was not me. I couldn't do that.

1526
02:47:24,000 --> 02:47:41,000
Because you have to be kind of like all things to all people and I wasn't that I was for the people who don't quote. And I knew what that took. And I was interested in people empowering people. I was interested in people becoming a part of the process just as I always had been.

1527
02:47:41,000 --> 02:47:47,000
So I realized that was not the vehicle that was cut out for me because I would never be able to raise that kind of money.

1528
02:47:47,000 --> 02:47:56,000
So that answered your question.

1529
02:47:56,000 --> 02:48:06,000
I was the town attorney in Irvington.

1530
02:48:06,000 --> 02:48:21,000
I was the town attorney in Irvington because I had a good friend Sara Bost who became mayor and she originally asked me to be council for the City Council where she was president of the council in Irvington.

1531
02:48:21,000 --> 02:48:36,000
Which is the town next over from New Town of about 50,000 mostly black. And then when she became mayor I helped her in her election. She asked me to be the town attorney.

1532
02:48:36,000 --> 02:48:51,000
So once she decided, excuse me, not to run again. I decided I was going to do something here and knew once again.

1533
02:48:51,000 --> 02:49:01,000
There was a program called Abbott v. Burke which was in trouble. It was always in trouble right from the onset. In 1981 a group called Education Law Center followed suit saying that you have to match the money state of New Jersey.

1534
02:49:01,000 --> 02:49:14,000
You have to match the money that the suburban schools are getting. You have to match the money that they're getting and put that into urban schools.

1535
02:49:14,000 --> 02:49:34,000
I don't know if they came up right because it's getting late in the day. I want to try it again.

1536
02:49:34,000 --> 02:50:03,000
Is that a claim of the state constitution? Well it was based on the state constitution which has thorough and efficient" in its language. And so the constitutional claim was upheld by seven white men over the age of 50 with a whole lot of money. They saw it. They said we have to have in the city the same amounts of money that they spend in the suburbs not just the average amount but the higher.

1537
02:50:03,000 --> 02:50:16,000
The higher suburbs of paying that's what we need to have real school reform and they prescribed a school reform program which has supplemental programs which if necessary and they always were you have to pay more state of New Jersey.

1538
02:50:16,000 --> 02:50:40,000
So now no governor since that time has agreed to that in total. Democrat Republican. So I said it's time to get the parents involved so to make a long story short I went to some foundations and I said we're going to build this organization that Rutgers based upon our ability to teach people how to become involved.

1539
02:50:40,000 --> 02:50:55,000
We're not going to have an organization but we're going to teach people how to get organized. So I have been able to bring all of my skills and all of my memories and all of my ability to help people strategize to do different things.

1540
02:50:55,000 --> 02:51:07,000
Whether it's on a little school basis or whether it's to help save the average program or whether it's to now helping young people to become involved in the process.

1541
02:51:07,000 --> 02:51:21,000
I said we've got older people involved as parents let's get the ultimate beneficiaries in here because when I was that age I was thinking about becoming a member of SNCC.

1542
02:51:21,000 --> 02:51:41,000
No such thoughts have been going on regularly on the part of young people today. They have been spontaneous outbursts. They have been people who want to mobilize to do different things. I'm not saying nobody's conscious because they are but the whole concept of organization has been lost.

1543
02:51:41,000 --> 02:51:56,000
It was lost when we put all of our eggs in the basket of electing black politicians and those black politicians turning around and destroyed the organizational base that brought them over.

1544
02:51:56,000 --> 02:52:19,000
So there's a whole brand new group of people out here don't know anything about SNCC and core and end cup and NAPA and how we got over and how we did what we did. So that's my job. I'm teaching a whole new generation what we did and everything I've been talking to you about for the last three hours we've been talking about in one way or another in those classes.

1545
02:52:19,000 --> 02:52:29,000
I am very excited about both groups. The parents getting organized more and more or not just because we're doing it parents organizing all the time.

1546
02:52:29,000 --> 02:52:49,000
But what we're trying to do is to help those parents who are so inclined to get involved. We're teaching them that there's a certain way you use information. There's a certain way that you position yourself. There's a certain set of strategies that you can use to make your presence more profitable in terms of the goals that you have.

1547
02:52:49,000 --> 02:53:03,000
With the young people who are saying to them, you have a voice and your voice deserves to be heard. And if you learn the skills of the media your voice can be amplified.

1548
02:53:03,000 --> 02:53:10,000
Now first part of that is the most difficult. A lot of young people have been so beat down they don't think they have a voice.

1549
02:53:10,000 --> 02:53:20,000
Must last that it should be heard. But we introduced that whole concept and once you open the door with them, boom, they walk through.

1550
02:53:20,000 --> 02:53:30,000
So now we got a whole lot of young advocates here who know how to speak. They know how to interview. They know how to use cameras. Not quite as expensive as that one.

1551
02:53:30,000 --> 02:53:47,000
They know how to put projects together. They know how to put we haven't taught them how to edit. Hopefully we'll do that this summer. It's a summer program on an intense basis five days four days a week and it's bringing in the fall. It's two days a week after school.

1552
02:53:47,000 --> 02:53:57,000
And they introduced a lot of documents that a lot of people have paid attention to short public service announcements to longer documentaries.

1553
02:53:57,000 --> 02:54:16,000
We've got some young people who have graduated and who now come back here and help us as interns. We've got some young people who have graduated and I meet them in the store or something they say, you know, because of that program, I went to college and now I'm really doing some advocacy things in college.

1554
02:54:16,000 --> 02:54:23,000
So we planted a seed that's that's being watered every day by the events of the time.

1555
02:54:23,000 --> 02:54:37,000
I know there's even more history, much more history that we could discuss, but today you have been just a remarkable generous and what a pleasure. So it's been an honor and a privilege. Thank you for such a generous and substantive contribution to this year.

1556
02:54:37,000 --> 02:54:51,000
Well, I hope everybody runs out and reads my book once it gets published. It's called Unfinished Agenda: Urban Politics in the Era of Black Power and hopefully it will be produced. It will be published by Smith Sony. So let's hope so.

1557
02:54:51,000 --> 02:54:58,000
Thank you so much.

1558
02:54:58,000 --> 02:55:07,000
This has been a presentation of the Library of Congress and the Smithsonian National Museum of African American History and Culture.
